00:44:49,622 --> 00:45:01,547
[SPEAKER_14]: Michelle Barkson, Christina Mastraboni, Anshika Hansen-Verma, and Jessica Parks, who had two hats during the task force meetings.

401
00:45:02,567 --> 00:45:07,590
[SPEAKER_14]: And for employees, we had the site coordinator at the McGlynn Elementary School, Kathy Hunt.

402
00:45:08,230 --> 00:45:13,192
[SPEAKER_14]: We had the site coordinator for the Roberts Elementary School, Kathleen, oh my goodness, I'm drawing a blank.

403
00:45:15,185 --> 00:45:16,305
[SPEAKER_14]: Guillaume, thank you.

404
00:45:16,686 --> 00:45:17,406
[SPEAKER_14]: Guillaume, thank you.

405
00:45:17,446 --> 00:45:18,066
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm so sorry.

406
00:45:18,926 --> 00:45:21,067
[SPEAKER_14]: Principal of the Mississippi, Nancy Sherman Hudson.

407
00:45:21,187 --> 00:45:23,548
[SPEAKER_14]: Principal of the Brooks, Shannon Demos.

408
00:45:24,708 --> 00:45:37,413
[SPEAKER_14]: Will Pippicelli, the communications director, myself, and for some of the meetings also, Megan Fidle-Carey, who was the program director of family and community engagement, also oversaw the program.

409
00:45:38,897 --> 00:45:51,144
[SPEAKER_14]: Megan will be stepping down, and so we are searching for new leadership, but the members of the task force really kind of lived the it takes a village mentality, and so I just wanted to make sure that I thank them.

410
00:45:51,684 --> 00:45:59,268
[SPEAKER_14]: And then the second part of the work has been this partnership with BASIC, which stands for Belmont Afterschool Enrichment Collaborative.

411
00:46:00,449 --> 00:46:07,613
[SPEAKER_14]: And so we began our partnership with them about a year ago, and they have just been tremendous.

412
00:46:08,814 --> 00:46:15,417
[SPEAKER_14]: And really, when you think of the word partnership, I feel like that has just encapsulated our work together.

413
00:46:15,437 --> 00:46:25,221
[SPEAKER_14]: They've been very thorough, but they've also been very honest, very transparent, very supportive, and very accommodating.

414
00:46:25,441 --> 00:46:30,923
[SPEAKER_14]: And so, that doesn't always happen when you're working with consultants or auditors.

415
00:46:30,983 --> 00:46:35,044
[SPEAKER_14]: And so, I just wanted to make sure that I thanked them very much for their work.

416
00:46:36,925 --> 00:46:41,569
[SPEAKER_14]: And with all that, I welcome the basic team to come up.

417
00:46:41,629 --> 00:46:58,904
[SPEAKER_14]: They are going to present their findings of their review of the Medford Public Schools afterschool programming, and they also are going to give us their recommendations and next steps for us to increase capacity and enrichment in our afterschool programming.

418
00:47:00,322 --> 00:47:00,782
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Dr. Galussi.

419
00:47:00,802 --> 00:47:01,523
[SPEAKER_14]: I leave it to you, Andrew.

420
00:47:01,543 --> 00:47:02,544
[SPEAKER_06]: I appreciate it.

421
00:47:02,584 --> 00:47:03,925
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you for the introduction.

422
00:47:03,965 --> 00:47:04,645
[SPEAKER_06]: That was wonderful.

423
00:47:05,726 --> 00:47:07,147
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm Andrew Manfred.

424
00:47:08,268 --> 00:47:18,836
[SPEAKER_06]: The first time speaking tonight, we'll popcorn back and forth with each of us sharing different elements of this presentation to you, and each of the folks will introduce themselves when they come up.

425
00:47:19,257 --> 00:47:22,099
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm the executive director of the Belmont Afterschool Enrichment Collaborative.

426
00:47:23,039 --> 00:47:27,222
[SPEAKER_06]: This, I want to signal at first, this has been a wonderful experience for us.

427
00:47:28,403 --> 00:47:47,154
[SPEAKER_06]: We, as Dr. Galussi said, began this partnership a year ago, and it's been tremendous to really build relationships with Dr. Galussi and her team, the staff at the programs, different faculty members of each of the schools,

428
00:47:48,375 --> 00:47:56,499
[SPEAKER_06]: and even individual parents, both serving on the task force, of course, but also folks that just cared to talk to us at each one of the programs.

429
00:47:57,320 --> 00:48:03,663
[SPEAKER_06]: I also want to take a moment to thank Dr. Galluzzi and her team, all the stakeholders who played a role in this process.

430
00:48:04,203 --> 00:48:05,984
[SPEAKER_06]: They are tremendous collaborators.

431
00:48:06,924 --> 00:48:15,468
[SPEAKER_06]: It is a difficult project to increase capacity of a program, much less four programs, and I think

432
00:48:17,349 --> 00:48:29,538
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not fully appreciated how new the field of out-of-school time programming really is, even when compared to what is still a relatively young public school system that we have in this country.

433
00:48:30,018 --> 00:48:40,705
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's not a small task to take on, and it does require a number of people to really go all in on the changes that need to be made.

434
00:48:40,985 --> 00:48:43,307
[SPEAKER_06]: So thank you for being a wonderful collaborator to work with.

435
00:48:44,328 --> 00:49:05,922
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to also flag that professionally as folks who have really dedicated our careers to out of school time programming, there's something that I'm really grateful for in being able to create a model for Medford public schools that we know works based on our own experience and to share that with the idea that it's going to benefit children and families.

436
00:49:06,802 --> 00:49:13,765
[SPEAKER_06]: Personally, I previously lived in Medford for 11 years, actually very, very close to this building.

437
00:49:13,885 --> 00:49:20,747
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's kind of personally gratifying to be part of a process where we're improving that experience for children and families.

438
00:49:22,568 --> 00:49:32,271
[SPEAKER_06]: Finally, I'd like to just say that as part of our report tonight, we are, of course, going to be focusing on details that need to be changed about the programs.

439
00:49:32,771 --> 00:49:35,132
[SPEAKER_06]: But before we get started, I just want to say that

440
00:49:36,352 --> 00:49:45,735
[SPEAKER_06]: The experience that we saw when visiting programs and talking to families really showed us how many warm, caring individuals there are working with the children in Medford.

441
00:49:46,475 --> 00:49:51,557
[SPEAKER_06]: And children are engaged in programming each day.

442
00:49:51,637 --> 00:49:55,679
[SPEAKER_06]: And for the most part, all of the systems that are in place are working.

443
00:49:56,759 --> 00:49:59,200
[SPEAKER_06]: They're just working for a smaller level than what Medford needs.

444
00:49:59,540 --> 00:50:02,281
[SPEAKER_06]: And so yes, we're going to be focusing on the changes that need to be made.

445
00:50:02,861 --> 00:50:05,403
[SPEAKER_06]: But please remember that there is a lot of good work to be done.

446
00:50:05,803 --> 00:50:21,713
[SPEAKER_06]: And even though, as I flagged, this is a difficult, not a difficult, but a big challenge to take on, the fact that we have so many caring people working on this gives me a lot of hope that this is going to be something that we put in place with a lot of success next year and growing success for years to come.

447
00:50:23,334 --> 00:50:25,675
[SPEAKER_06]: With that, I'm going to turn things over to my colleague, Michael.

448
00:50:26,576 --> 00:50:26,936
[SPEAKER_19]: Hi, everyone.

449
00:50:28,843 --> 00:50:29,784
[SPEAKER_19]: We can hear me, right?

450
00:50:29,904 --> 00:50:30,084
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes.

451
00:50:30,225 --> 00:50:30,805
[SPEAKER_19]: OK, thank you.

452
00:50:31,726 --> 00:50:35,971
[SPEAKER_19]: So I'm just going to frame us a little bit for the rest of our presentation here.

453
00:50:36,912 --> 00:50:39,575
[SPEAKER_19]: In a moment, we're going to talk about our phase one.

454
00:50:39,595 --> 00:50:41,778
[SPEAKER_19]: Oh, Michael Clark, I'm sorry.

455
00:50:41,818 --> 00:50:45,082
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm the site director for Basics Maynard Programs.

456
00:50:45,142 --> 00:50:47,505
[SPEAKER_19]: That's at the Fowler Middle School and the Green Medal Elementary School.

457
00:50:47,525 --> 00:50:47,785
[SPEAKER_19]: Thank you.

458
00:50:49,807 --> 00:51:00,290
[SPEAKER_19]: So we're gonna start this evening by talking about our methodology to collect data to inform our recommendations and then I'll turn it over to my colleague Annie who will give a high level overview of that data.

459
00:51:01,280 --> 00:51:12,606
[SPEAKER_19]: We'll then move into the observed challenges that kind of emerged out of that data collection and then give specific actionable recommendations to address each of those challenge areas.

460
00:51:13,667 --> 00:51:23,532
[SPEAKER_19]: We'll then move into the specific capacity increases that we're recommending for the district and then give a sample schedule about how to accommodate the increase in those student numbers.

461
00:51:24,152 --> 00:51:29,454
[SPEAKER_19]: And then last, we'll present tuition rates for you all to approve today.

462
00:51:30,134 --> 00:51:36,797
[SPEAKER_19]: That's for after-school programming and then potential full-day programming like February and April vacation camps, potential PD coverage as well.

463
00:51:37,517 --> 00:51:38,938
[SPEAKER_19]: And then Angela will wrap us up.

464
00:51:38,978 --> 00:51:41,699
[SPEAKER_19]: And then if there's any questions from the committee, we're happy to answer.

465
00:51:41,719 --> 00:51:43,800
[SPEAKER_19]: Go ahead and go to the next slide.

466
00:51:48,038 --> 00:51:51,659
[SPEAKER_19]: So, we prioritized four main areas of data collection.

467
00:51:51,839 --> 00:51:52,979
[SPEAKER_19]: The first was site visits.

468
00:51:53,199 --> 00:52:01,161
[SPEAKER_19]: We conducted 13 site visits overall, primarily focused at the Brooks and the Roberts as the two schools with the highest wait lists for after school programming.

469
00:52:02,021 --> 00:52:16,905
[SPEAKER_19]: We did 20 stakeholder interviews, and that was with administrators, staff, with families, with kiddos in the program and without kids in the program, as well as some members of the task force that Dr. Glusi mentioned earlier.

470
00:52:17,665 --> 00:52:27,810
[SPEAKER_19]: We launched a community survey which had just under 400 respondents to really get a picture of the needs from the community in after-school programming, as well as their hopes for after-school.

471
00:52:28,871 --> 00:52:39,696
[SPEAKER_19]: And then we had several data collection meetings with other administrators, such as the human resource director, financial director, to really get a full picture of what after-school operations look like as is.

472
00:52:40,637 --> 00:52:45,479
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm going to turn it over to Annie.

473
00:52:50,347 --> 00:52:50,907
[SPEAKER_25]: Hi, good evening.

474
00:52:50,967 --> 00:52:52,088
[SPEAKER_25]: My name is Annie Gladfelter.

475
00:52:52,108 --> 00:52:54,068
[SPEAKER_25]: I'm the director of impact for the organization.

476
00:52:54,088 --> 00:52:59,130
[SPEAKER_25]: I do actually a lot of program consulting for the organization, specifically about programming.

477
00:52:59,830 --> 00:53:04,012
[SPEAKER_25]: So you'll be hearing from me a bit later today as I speak to that.

478
00:53:04,512 --> 00:53:10,434
[SPEAKER_25]: But in speaking about our data summary, we did a much thorough presentation about our data for the task force.

479
00:53:11,174 --> 00:53:17,997
[SPEAKER_25]: But right now, for tonight, we're just going to focus on a generalization about what the data came back from all the methodology that we used.

480
00:53:18,898 --> 00:53:28,822
[SPEAKER_25]: As Michael just said, we really focused on interviews, observations, and a landscape survey to really give, to inform our recommendations that you're going to hear about tonight.

481
00:53:29,483 --> 00:53:34,145
[SPEAKER_25]: And in our summary, we comprised this into kind of four categories, the family experience,

482
00:53:34,525 --> 00:53:38,286
[SPEAKER_25]: program experience, a student experience, and a staff experience.

483
00:53:39,326 --> 00:53:54,710
[SPEAKER_25]: From the family experience, we really, you know, we took from interviews and the survey and really found out overall that the biggest thing that we heard back from our families was that the capacity issue was their biggest complaint or the issue most facing the community.

484
00:53:55,270 --> 00:54:04,212
[SPEAKER_25]: And that also that there was also a desire to have better transparency about wait lists and better overall communication.

485
00:54:05,253 --> 00:54:12,502
[SPEAKER_25]: For our internal families who we interviewed, we did hear that they were really satisfied with the programming that their children were receiving.

486
00:54:13,443 --> 00:54:19,750
[SPEAKER_25]: What they were reporting about was that they had children that were happy and that were coming home, you know, satisfied with their day.

487
00:54:20,151 --> 00:54:24,295
[SPEAKER_25]: And for them, really kind of hitting the mark about being supervised and well cared for.

488
00:54:24,856 --> 00:54:41,889
[SPEAKER_25]: And for the external families that we spoke to, most of what they spoke about was just the lack of transparency about the process, and they just wanted a better view into the procedures and understanding better about how wait lists happen, how the registration process happens, and so just kind of having a better system for that.

489
00:54:43,090 --> 00:54:46,833
[SPEAKER_25]: As far as program experience, this really was informed by our observation.

490
00:54:47,954 --> 00:54:53,578
[SPEAKER_25]: We really saw that there was enough spaces actually for an expansion of capacity at our schools.

491
00:54:54,279 --> 00:54:57,201
[SPEAKER_25]: But what we noted was that the spaces could be better utilized.

492
00:54:57,741 --> 00:55:04,166
[SPEAKER_25]: And so part of what you're going to hear in our recommendations tonight is how to use those spaces better to accommodate for more students.

493
00:55:04,606 --> 00:55:11,712
[SPEAKER_25]: And also what we found out from our interviews is that there's a school administration is really supportive of any structural changes that need to occur.

494
00:55:12,272 --> 00:55:14,654
[SPEAKER_25]: to support those capacity expansions.

495
00:55:15,755 --> 00:55:20,919
[SPEAKER_25]: As for the student experience, we didn't interview any students and all of this was informed just by observations.

496
00:55:21,760 --> 00:55:28,605
[SPEAKER_25]: And that what we found was that, again, students were happy, well behaved, you know, seemed interactive.

497
00:55:29,025 --> 00:55:35,430
[SPEAKER_25]: But overall, we found that students were, that there was a little bit of a lack of student engagement.

498
00:55:36,311 --> 00:55:40,756
[SPEAKER_25]: quality of the activities that students were engaged in was a little bit on the lower level.

499
00:55:41,497 --> 00:55:53,131
[SPEAKER_25]: And so part of what you're going to hear tonight is some of our programmatic recommendations because we do worry a little bit about what expansion of the programs could look like as far as the program quality and student experience.

500
00:55:54,107 --> 00:55:59,009
[SPEAKER_25]: And as for our staff experience, again, we heard from staff that were really satisfied.

501
00:55:59,069 --> 00:56:07,492
[SPEAKER_25]: They loved their jobs, reporting really great experiences with the students and their families, having great working relationships with their colleagues.

502
00:56:08,553 --> 00:56:16,836
[SPEAKER_25]: But overall, what we did find, which was concerning for us, and you'll hear a bit more about this tonight, was a lack of prep and planning time.

503
00:56:16,936 --> 00:56:19,417
[SPEAKER_25]: And that because of the hours in which they work,

504
00:56:20,277 --> 00:56:34,848
[SPEAKER_25]: There is actually no time built into their schedules to plan, and often staff reported that they had to plan outside of work hours, often on evenings and weekends, and that time wasn't compensated for, which was reflected again back into the programmatic experience of students.

505
00:56:35,828 --> 00:56:44,715
[SPEAKER_25]: And that, again, staff reporting that they had a really great experience, and most reporting great relationships with their site coordinators, however,

506
00:56:45,516 --> 00:56:52,365
[SPEAKER_25]: noting that, again, because of limited time, there was very limited formal feedback or structure for that.

507
00:56:53,026 --> 00:56:59,255
[SPEAKER_25]: And that was really what we kind of took, and that will be informing as you hear, as we go forward in our recommendations to be addressed tonight.

508
00:56:59,775 --> 00:57:00,036
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

509
00:57:03,927 --> 00:57:09,392
[SPEAKER_19]: So as we took a look at the data, kind of five key challenge areas emerged.

510
00:57:10,313 --> 00:57:16,898
[SPEAKER_19]: And so as we go forward, we'll address, kind of define each of these challenge areas and then give our specific recommendations for them.

511
00:57:17,179 --> 00:57:23,724
[SPEAKER_19]: I'd also just make a pitch here that we've sent in our full report, which has some additional recommendations.

512
00:57:23,744 --> 00:57:26,867
[SPEAKER_19]: So this presentation is just going to highlight a few that we feel like are the most important.

513
00:57:27,347 --> 00:57:30,270
[SPEAKER_19]: And I'll turn it over to Andrew, who's going to discuss the first one, strategic vision.

514
00:57:33,621 --> 00:57:34,562
[SPEAKER_06]: Thanks, Michael.

515
00:57:34,782 --> 00:57:41,089
[SPEAKER_06]: As we mentioned at the beginning, we were really tasked with developing a model for Medford Public Schools.

516
00:57:41,730 --> 00:57:51,360
[SPEAKER_06]: And the most important first step in developing that model is to create a position, a leadership position, with whom this model will

517
00:57:52,548 --> 00:57:56,730
[SPEAKER_06]: be defined, will grow and develop, and will be communicated over time.

518
00:57:57,811 --> 00:58:08,775
[SPEAKER_06]: So, you know, we're talking about a person who can really own that vision and carry it forward for Medford Public Schools.

519
00:58:11,359 --> 00:58:25,273
[SPEAKER_06]: To create that vision, as part of that process, we have identified, as Michael flagged, some payroll discrepancies, communication and wait list management issues, some inconsistencies in executive leadership.

520
00:58:27,215 --> 00:58:37,083
[SPEAKER_06]: These issues cause a real shortfall in the district's ability to craft that strategic plan, that strategic vision for after school.

521
00:58:37,783 --> 00:58:45,930
[SPEAKER_06]: And we see that in the communication, we see that in the professional relationships and kind of the downstream effects that it has on the program staff.

522
00:58:46,550 --> 00:58:51,072
[SPEAKER_06]: So these pieces need to be the first steps that we take.

523
00:58:52,313 --> 00:58:55,074
[SPEAKER_06]: As Michael flagged as well, we've got four action steps here.

524
00:58:55,094 --> 00:58:59,295
[SPEAKER_06]: There are more in our report, but I want to communicate these four priorities to you.

525
00:58:59,315 --> 00:59:04,478
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, these are the first steps that MPS takes in this process.

526
00:59:05,278 --> 00:59:12,344
[SPEAKER_06]: So the first is to define and adopt a district-wide programming philosophy through a process.

527
00:59:12,424 --> 00:59:25,495
[SPEAKER_06]: That is using our model and having every stakeholder in afterschool understand and adopt that vision to guide them for Medford Public Schools afterschool programming.

528
00:59:26,376 --> 00:59:31,720
[SPEAKER_06]: We need to then establish a single accountable leader in whom that vision is going to reside.

529
00:59:32,561 --> 00:59:41,665
[SPEAKER_06]: And as the program grows and needs change, that person uses that vision to make those changes, to inform the decisions that they make that are needed for the programs.

530
00:59:43,346 --> 00:59:49,809
[SPEAKER_06]: And they're also, as I said before, tasked with communicating that effectively to the community.

531
00:59:50,797 --> 00:59:57,220
[SPEAKER_06]: The good news about this step is that a lot of those first two steps, a lot of this work has been done already.

532
00:59:57,660 --> 01:00:03,462
[SPEAKER_06]: The first piece is our model from which we'll draw that vision.

533
01:00:03,922 --> 01:00:11,105
[SPEAKER_06]: And the second piece, a job description for this accountable leader, is one that we drafted for Dr. Galluzzi.

534
01:00:11,125 --> 01:00:13,526
[SPEAKER_06]: It's what we call the managing director of programs.

535
01:00:13,546 --> 01:00:18,488
[SPEAKER_06]: And there's already some work involved in finding that person and getting them in this role.

536
01:00:19,697 --> 01:00:32,184
[SPEAKER_06]: Next we have developing and continuing to revise a registration and wait list process and communicating that strategy out to the community.

537
01:00:32,564 --> 01:00:43,630
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, of course, in a lot of these tasks and responsibilities that we're going to talk about, that responsibility will fall to this managing director over time.

538
01:00:43,830 --> 01:00:46,872
[SPEAKER_06]: But again, the good news is, with the help of the task force,

539
01:00:47,194 --> 01:00:52,279
[SPEAKER_06]: with the communications director, we've already taken steps toward that as well.

540
01:00:52,520 --> 01:01:07,015
[SPEAKER_06]: So drafting that language, understanding what the vision is, how we can communicate this effectively so families understand that work is being done, and they'll see big steps next year to start making this not a problem for so many folks in the community.

541
01:01:08,608 --> 01:01:24,024
[SPEAKER_06]: Finally, the last piece in this category that I want to mention tonight is we're making the recommendation to transition each of what was previously known as a site coordinator for each of the programs into a site director role.

542
01:01:24,665 --> 01:01:28,808
[SPEAKER_06]: And those folks would report directly to the managing director.

543
01:01:29,288 --> 01:01:35,852
[SPEAKER_06]: This is very important because it is, and this is a segue into what Mike was going to talk about in the moment.

544
01:01:36,272 --> 01:01:47,019
[SPEAKER_06]: One of the biggest pieces that we need to establish for after school is increased capacity for leadership, increased capacity for managing, and increased capacity for administration.

545
01:01:47,619 --> 01:01:58,525
[SPEAKER_06]: So a lot of that is not happening while program is happening, and to the expense of other things that folks should be focused on in the moment when working with children.

546
01:01:58,545 --> 01:02:01,167
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll turn this over to Michael next.

547
01:02:04,704 --> 01:02:12,070
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes, so our next area of challenge that has to be addressed is this management and administrative capacity.

548
01:02:12,270 --> 01:02:26,663
[SPEAKER_19]: And really the key highlight in this area is that as it stands, leaders don't have structured time to manage their teams and to build the kind of processes, the kind of systems that's gonna support growth as we look toward the next year.

549
01:02:28,223 --> 01:02:34,586
[SPEAKER_19]: So, in addition to changing that title from site coordinator to site director, we want to make this a full-time position.

550
01:02:35,106 --> 01:02:40,028
[SPEAKER_19]: And that's going to really give that structured time for this individual to manage their teams, right?

551
01:02:40,048 --> 01:02:46,811
[SPEAKER_19]: To have the time available to think ahead, anticipate problems, work with their staff, and build and grow.

552
01:02:47,252 --> 01:02:51,633
[SPEAKER_19]: It's also going to give the managing director a team for themselves, right?

553
01:02:51,653 --> 01:02:55,015
[SPEAKER_19]: They're going to have other individuals that they can delegate to as they're owning this vision.

554
01:02:55,595 --> 01:03:14,593
[SPEAKER_19]: And for building staff themselves, principals, for the facilities team, teachers, there's a key person in each building who has the time to field questions, to build relationships, to understand the priorities of each individual school and make sure that they're carried over into the after school day.

555
01:03:15,955 --> 01:03:21,640
[SPEAKER_19]: Second, we were recommending that we want to standardize the onboarding and orientation process.

556
01:03:22,061 --> 01:03:38,917
[SPEAKER_19]: We really want to make sure that as we go into this next year that everyone on the afterschool team has a clear understanding of that shared mission and orientation, an orientation where we're all together establishing those expectations is going to be the best tool for us to really hit the ground running.

557
01:03:40,379 --> 01:03:47,846
[SPEAKER_19]: Last, we're recommending that each individual site implement a daily staff meeting with as many individuals as possible.

558
01:03:48,246 --> 01:03:55,413
[SPEAKER_19]: A lot of folks that work for the after school team are paraprofessionals or have other responsibilities during the school day, which is going to make that very difficult.

559
01:03:55,873 --> 01:03:58,376
[SPEAKER_19]: our own teams and our organization as basic.

560
01:03:58,796 --> 01:04:18,736
[SPEAKER_19]: We experienced this problem as well, but making sure there's some structured time each day for as many staff as possible to work on the day-to-day and really give our site director, the recommended site director, the space to manage their staff, to bring staff together and work together each day.

561
01:04:20,037 --> 01:04:26,261
[SPEAKER_19]: This leads into our next category, which is staff accountability and continuous improvement.

562
01:04:26,701 --> 01:04:31,724
[SPEAKER_19]: So we've implemented some tools to bring us together.

563
01:04:31,764 --> 01:04:33,105
[SPEAKER_19]: We've given ourselves that capacity.

564
01:04:33,125 --> 01:04:41,410
[SPEAKER_19]: Now we have to make sure we're holding our individual staff accountable, not just to their performance, but to their own personal continued growth and the program's growth.

565
01:04:42,230 --> 01:04:51,532
[SPEAKER_19]: And so from our observations, from our site visits and things, we didn't really see a clear unifying structure for staff accountability.

566
01:04:52,032 --> 01:05:00,673
[SPEAKER_19]: So the first thing we want to do is we want to implement a calendar of professional developments that occurs annually for all staff to participate in.

567
01:05:01,714 --> 01:05:05,974
[SPEAKER_19]: In our report, we've outlined some specific trainings that we think are really key.

568
01:05:06,554 --> 01:05:08,555
[SPEAKER_19]: So you can dive into that literature as well.

569
01:05:09,535 --> 01:05:18,785
[SPEAKER_19]: Each staff member should have, you know, that shared vision of how we're going to approach programming, and that should be equalized, so to speak, across all sites, right?

570
01:05:18,805 --> 01:05:21,027
[SPEAKER_19]: And we're doing that work at the beginning of the year.

571
01:05:22,168 --> 01:05:27,529
[SPEAKER_19]: Next, we want to launch a coaching and evaluation system for each individual staff member.

572
01:05:27,549 --> 01:05:38,191
[SPEAKER_19]: And so site directors would take the responsibility of meeting with their team and using several different tools, like one-on-one meetings, like observations, performance reviews.

573
01:05:38,611 --> 01:05:50,113
[SPEAKER_19]: And really here, we want to give that director the tools necessary to be providing sufficient feedback, but also spaces for staff to be giving feedback up.

574
01:05:50,713 --> 01:05:54,975
[SPEAKER_19]: And that's another, the daily staff meeting connects to that as well.

575
01:05:55,615 --> 01:06:02,598
[SPEAKER_19]: So I have the time as an individual staff member to give feedback in a one-on-one to my director, and they have time to give that to me.

576
01:06:02,958 --> 01:06:10,241
[SPEAKER_19]: I have a space each day, something happened to me after school that I need to bring up, or I'm not even sure I need to bring up, I can do that at the staff meeting.

577
01:06:10,261 --> 01:06:15,143
[SPEAKER_19]: And so we're these standardized, structured times for any staff member to do that.

578
01:06:16,042 --> 01:06:21,985
[SPEAKER_19]: And this really builds toward the overall goal here of promoting a culture of initiative, right?

579
01:06:22,045 --> 01:06:32,890
[SPEAKER_19]: So all of these things blend together, and we really want to give staff clear expectations about how they can grow and what areas that they should be focusing on, focusing their energy on.

580
01:06:34,831 --> 01:06:39,073
[SPEAKER_19]: Next, Annie's going to talk a little bit about program quality and kind of our specific recommendations there.

581
01:06:42,074 --> 01:06:43,055
[SPEAKER_26]: Oh, sorry.

582
01:06:43,095 --> 01:06:43,535
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you.

583
01:06:45,353 --> 01:06:57,863
[SPEAKER_25]: So yes, our biggest recommendations around program quality really stem from the concept that if these programs are going to grow, really we need to give substantive experiences for students.

584
01:06:58,464 --> 01:07:02,768
[SPEAKER_25]: A big kind of dilemma that I think programs face is that if students aren't engaged,

585
01:07:03,208 --> 01:07:17,557
[SPEAKER_25]: Even though children are having a good enough experience and that they're well behaved right now, one thing that we can predict is that we will see a spike in student behaviors and that it will be harder to actually keep kids engaged.

586
01:07:17,977 --> 01:07:25,222
[SPEAKER_25]: And so the programs as they are are fine enough, but we do need to make a higher investment into the overall quality.

587
01:07:25,942 --> 01:07:29,346
[SPEAKER_25]: And part of what we're recommending is some structural changes to the program.

588
01:07:30,187 --> 01:07:41,421
[SPEAKER_25]: And part of that being that right now, if you're not aware, currently students move by grade groups from space to space and engage in specific activities led by their group leaders.

589
01:07:42,061 --> 01:07:45,223
[SPEAKER_25]: who are then required to plan each one of those activities.

590
01:07:45,963 --> 01:08:00,610
[SPEAKER_25]: Part of what we found is that, again, because of a lack of planning time, a lot of the activities were lacking as far as quality, a little bit disjointed, and they weren't always engaging students to the highest level.

591
01:08:01,891 --> 01:08:07,954
[SPEAKER_25]: And sometimes they almost felt like time fillers because staff didn't have enough time to prep and plan.

592
01:08:08,714 --> 01:08:18,644
[SPEAKER_25]: And we also found that because of the grade groups, that kids were really limited in their peer interactions, and that especially as students got older, they really felt confined to those peer groups.

593
01:08:19,425 --> 01:08:29,534
[SPEAKER_25]: So what we're going to kind of, below is what I'm going to kind of offer to you as some recommendations as what we think would help improve the programs, especially, more generally, but especially for those as they grow in size.

594
01:08:30,656 --> 01:08:36,621
[SPEAKER_25]: Our big recommendation, and again we also heard this from surveying of parents of interest, is we really want to prioritize time outside.

595
01:08:37,302 --> 01:08:49,034
[SPEAKER_25]: It's really going to help for high capacity numbers, but also it is what we know to be best practice for children as far as giving them opportunities to solve real world problems with their peers.

596
01:08:49,754 --> 01:08:54,018
[SPEAKER_25]: So really trying to find a programmatic model that prioritizes that time outside.

597
01:08:55,039 --> 01:09:08,289
[SPEAKER_25]: We also really want to emphasize higher quality lesson planning, activities that are really thematic and project-based and have kind of longer-term goals in mind and are really driven by student interests.

598
01:09:09,150 --> 01:09:17,976
[SPEAKER_25]: And with that, kind of this idea of creating two to three new full-time positions, which we're actually terming specialists.

599
01:09:18,717 --> 01:09:22,940
[SPEAKER_25]: These would be lead educators in the curriculum planning and implementation.

600
01:09:23,700 --> 01:09:29,184
[SPEAKER_25]: Some sites were recommending two, some were recommending three, again, based on the size, and you'll hear a little bit more about that.

601
01:09:30,185 --> 01:09:37,049
[SPEAKER_25]: But these would be specialists in the specialties of sports, STEAM, and kindergarten.

602
01:09:37,469 --> 01:09:48,197
[SPEAKER_25]: And again, they would have the main priority of planning in their specialty field and receiving students to engage in those lessons and activities at that higher level.

603
01:09:49,017 --> 01:09:52,640
[SPEAKER_25]: And with that, we would be actually adjusting the program structure.

604
01:09:53,560 --> 01:10:05,108
[SPEAKER_25]: to move away from the idea of grade groups and group sort of movement and have multi-age grouping and allow much more student choice based programming.

605
01:10:05,549 --> 01:10:09,792
[SPEAKER_25]: And so what you're going to be able to see a little bit more tonight is about kind of what that student schedule looks like.

606
01:10:09,832 --> 01:10:12,714
[SPEAKER_25]: So how do you be able to offer multiple ages

607
01:10:13,554 --> 01:10:15,476
[SPEAKER_25]: a variety of options with that.

608
01:10:16,256 --> 01:10:22,501
[SPEAKER_25]: And then with those also curriculum specialists, this idea that we would be training them on how to do high-level implementation.

609
01:10:23,082 --> 01:10:40,455
[SPEAKER_25]: And again, the big emphasis being here is that we want to make sure that we're creating a lot of great learning experiences that students are opting into, are driven to want to participate in, having that choice, and that they're individuals who have that planning time and that interest to really drive that learning.

610
01:10:41,196 --> 01:10:41,476
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

611
01:10:46,040 --> 01:10:52,045
[SPEAKER_19]: So our last challenge area is all about the day-to-day operations of each individual site.

612
01:10:52,065 --> 01:10:58,271
[SPEAKER_19]: So our recommendations here are about, you know, more detailed on the ground things that we observed.

613
01:10:59,292 --> 01:11:09,921
[SPEAKER_19]: So the first thing we're recommending is to delegate to a different staff member the responsibility of dismissal and managing student movement throughout the day.

614
01:11:10,261 --> 01:11:16,406
[SPEAKER_19]: And the reason behind that is we really want to free up the recommended site directors from that responsibility.

615
01:11:16,986 --> 01:11:18,127
[SPEAKER_19]: We want them on the floor.

616
01:11:18,147 --> 01:11:23,651
[SPEAKER_19]: We want them embedded in programming, observing staff, and not tied to parent pickup.

617
01:11:24,992 --> 01:11:28,976
[SPEAKER_19]: Second, and Annie touched on this, really using spaces differently.

618
01:11:29,516 --> 01:11:34,640
[SPEAKER_19]: And what I'd like to add to this is how you're organizing your staff to that space.

619
01:11:35,020 --> 01:11:36,942
[SPEAKER_19]: So rather than having them follow each

620
01:11:37,702 --> 01:11:45,887
[SPEAKER_19]: follow a designated group of students, but tying them to a space and allowing students to move in and out of that space.

621
01:11:47,048 --> 01:11:51,411
[SPEAKER_19]: This helps really motivate staff too, because they can pursue their own interests.

622
01:11:51,951 --> 01:11:56,894
[SPEAKER_19]: Instead of having to be part of a STEM project when I'm personally, that's not my bag.

623
01:11:57,234 --> 01:12:03,178
[SPEAKER_19]: But I can pursue my interests, I can try to put together art projects, I can move down that career path.

624
01:12:03,958 --> 01:12:14,046
[SPEAKER_19]: If I'm more of a sport person, I can be put in the gym, placed in the gym, and students can come move in and out of that space throughout the day as opposed to me following them.

625
01:12:15,047 --> 01:12:25,435
[SPEAKER_19]: Last, we want to implement some specific tools to really make sure that as we make this kind of schedule change that we're prioritizing safety.

626
01:12:25,755 --> 01:12:32,961
[SPEAKER_19]: So some key details there would be making sure that each site and every staff member has a radio on them to be communicating about student movement.

627
01:12:33,361 --> 01:12:36,343
[SPEAKER_19]: but also implementing some tracking tools like an activity log.

628
01:12:36,623 --> 01:12:41,586
[SPEAKER_19]: This is something we use in our own programs where students are responsible for signing into this space.

629
01:12:42,106 --> 01:12:46,169
[SPEAKER_19]: And then that front desk individual gets a live update about where that student is.

630
01:12:46,569 --> 01:12:50,131
[SPEAKER_19]: If they're deciding to leave, they're signing out, signing into wherever they're landing.

631
01:12:51,111 --> 01:12:55,894
[SPEAKER_19]: So these are some kind of the first steps to really make sure that we're executing our program safely.

632
01:12:56,795 --> 01:13:00,477
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm going to turn it over to Andrew, who's going to talk about the capacity increases.

633
01:13:03,177 --> 01:13:03,537
[SPEAKER_06]: Thanks, Michael.

634
01:13:04,938 --> 01:13:31,259
[SPEAKER_06]: So our first, our goal in coming up with a capacity increase for next year, in speaking to Dr. Galussi and talking and working with the task force, is to take the most aggressive approach possible, but to make sure that's limited by what is achievable in the small amount of time that we have between this year and next year, and then in turn is also financially viable one year to the next.

635
01:13:32,957 --> 01:13:42,560
[SPEAKER_06]: From that kind of North Star guiding us, we looked at the first priority of making sure that no folks who are currently working at the programs are going to lose their jobs.

636
01:13:43,340 --> 01:13:47,061
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't want to be scaling back, you know, before we've actually put a new model in place.

637
01:13:47,481 --> 01:13:57,904
[SPEAKER_06]: So taking that current staff that we have at each of the programs and thinking again about that specialist position that Annie talked about, adding two or three specialists at each site.

638
01:13:58,884 --> 01:14:01,145
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'll just quickly kind of break that down for everybody.

639
01:14:01,705 --> 01:14:06,467
[SPEAKER_06]: At each of the four, all four of these sites serve students between kindergarten and fifth grade.

640
01:14:06,947 --> 01:14:14,009
[SPEAKER_06]: So one of the positions that we recommend is a first hire, what we call a kindergarten specialist.

641
01:14:14,329 --> 01:14:16,370
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is a manager for that kindergarten room.

642
01:14:16,450 --> 01:14:20,131
[SPEAKER_06]: It's developmentally appropriate to have them separate from the greater grade.

643
01:14:20,812 --> 01:14:21,272
[SPEAKER_06]: Oops, excuse me.

644
01:14:22,012 --> 01:14:26,934
[SPEAKER_06]: And the other two positions, so that's true for all four of the schools.

645
01:14:27,915 --> 01:14:33,277
[SPEAKER_06]: For the other positions, we would like each site to start with what we call a sports specialist.

646
01:14:34,118 --> 01:14:50,465
[SPEAKER_06]: So for our purposes in understanding how we can serve the most number of students, again to think about capacity as being our driving force here, how can we make sure we're serving the highest number of students in spaces that are equipped to serve a large number and to appeal to a broad group?

647
01:14:50,865 --> 01:14:55,248
[SPEAKER_06]: making sure there's someone on the staff who's planning and implementing a sports curriculum.

648
01:14:55,708 --> 01:15:10,939
[SPEAKER_06]: And when I say sports, that ranges from what you'd really look at at the younger grades from being a PE experience for most of the younger levels and kind of graduating into a little bit more of what you might find in rec sports by fourth and fifth grade.

649
01:15:12,233 --> 01:15:17,997
[SPEAKER_06]: For any program that already can meet that need with an individual staff member, that priority could be shifted.

650
01:15:18,677 --> 01:15:23,540
[SPEAKER_06]: Our number two recommendation is for a STEAM specialist position.

651
01:15:23,560 --> 01:15:31,566
[SPEAKER_06]: So for those who are not used to the term STEAM, it's combined the science, technology, engineering, and math with an arts piece.

652
01:15:31,966 --> 01:15:37,070
[SPEAKER_06]: So that person is designing and implementing curriculum in that domain every single day.

653
01:15:37,970 --> 01:15:39,652
[SPEAKER_06]: Any flag for us that

654
01:15:40,252 --> 01:15:58,954
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't feel that the size of the groups at each of the four schools, because of the large difference between McGlynn and Missituck at the 100 level, which is really going to meet the full need that we feel that there is at those schools based on our landscape analysis, compared with

655
01:15:59,830 --> 01:16:05,518
[SPEAKER_06]: The Roberts at 150 and the Brooks at 195, those warrant having that extra specialist.

656
01:16:06,960 --> 01:16:16,392
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a matter of making sure that you have space for all the students and something that can hold their interest and sustain their attention for that larger group.

657
01:16:17,794 --> 01:16:26,298
[SPEAKER_06]: So, that's the Kindergarten and Sports Specialists at McGlynn and Missituck, Kindergarten, Sports, and STEAM Specialists at Roberts and Brooks.

658
01:16:27,219 --> 01:16:41,326
[SPEAKER_06]: From there, from that level of staff investment, we layered on the operational pieces that Michael talked about to say like, okay, what programmatic and kind of space changes can we make?

659
01:16:42,767 --> 01:16:47,189
[SPEAKER_06]: And after kind of analyzing each of those, we're very comfortable with an increase next year

660
01:16:48,109 --> 01:16:49,811
[SPEAKER_06]: up to the levels that you see on this slide.

661
01:16:51,492 --> 01:17:00,998
[SPEAKER_06]: This, I wanna flag that this isn't, from what we understand, you know, the need to be, based mostly on the survey, but also other information that we gathered through this process.

662
01:17:01,458 --> 01:17:03,800
[SPEAKER_06]: This isn't the full need in Medford.

663
01:17:04,240 --> 01:17:07,562
[SPEAKER_06]: This would be a multi-phased increase over time.

664
01:17:07,922 --> 01:17:13,746
[SPEAKER_06]: But again, we don't want to set up a situation that's going to, you know, not be achievable in the first year.

665
01:17:14,647 --> 01:17:16,508
[SPEAKER_06]: So, you know, making this jump,

666
01:17:17,008 --> 01:17:25,111
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, from 120 to 195, a 75 student increase at the Brooks alone is substantial.

667
01:17:25,851 --> 01:17:27,832
[SPEAKER_06]: And we play that across other programs.

668
01:17:27,912 --> 01:17:31,193
[SPEAKER_06]: We're adding a number of seats to our programs for next year.

669
01:17:31,213 --> 01:17:35,654
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm going to switch slides.

670
01:17:37,215 --> 01:17:39,955
[SPEAKER_06]: Actually, I'm going to pass off to Annie for the next one.

671
01:17:50,068 --> 01:17:55,671
[SPEAKER_25]: I know the picture for the sample schedule is a little bit small, so bear with me, but I hope you can follow along.

672
01:17:56,612 --> 01:18:03,955
[SPEAKER_25]: This is an example schedule that we wanted to share with you, specifically trying to highlight what a multi-age programming model would look like.

673
01:18:04,876 --> 01:18:14,821
[SPEAKER_25]: I do want to highlight that we actually do have kindergarten separated, and as Andrew referenced, of kindergarten specialists who would have the responsibility of really owning that kindergarten experience.

674
01:18:15,421 --> 01:18:17,843
[SPEAKER_25]: in many ways, like the way a kindergarten teacher would.

675
01:18:18,503 --> 01:18:31,550
[SPEAKER_25]: And so because we think developmentally, kindergartens really still need that kind of small classroom model experience, need to kind of be with their own group, really with a teacher that really understands that age group.

676
01:18:32,331 --> 01:18:42,517
[SPEAKER_25]: They will continue to have a classroom experience, a designated room where they get to have activities that are geared towards kindergarten, and they will go to certain spaces as a kindergarten group.

677
01:18:43,437 --> 01:18:45,358
[SPEAKER_25]: to have that, again, that kindergarten experience.

678
01:18:45,818 --> 01:18:55,222
[SPEAKER_25]: However, if you kind of pan over and look through the first through fifth grade, they're slightly grade group, but generally the concept is that first through fifth grade is all together.

679
01:18:55,723 --> 01:19:02,466
[SPEAKER_25]: And if you look at the space column, you can actually get a sense from how the activities in that space column are listed.

680
01:19:03,126 --> 01:19:04,787
[SPEAKER_25]: What we've sort of done here is tried to

681
01:19:05,567 --> 01:19:15,716
[SPEAKER_25]: visualize different activities that could be occurring over the course of the day and the various spaces that would be utilized to have those activities happening.

682
01:19:16,797 --> 01:19:31,791
[SPEAKER_25]: In a first through fifth grade experience, oftentimes those students would be intermixed, but specifically on activities where the idea of a six or seven-year-old being with a 10-year-old would make sense, where it would be things like,

683
01:19:32,091 --> 01:19:38,456
[SPEAKER_25]: playing outside on the playground or playing in the cafeteria for board games or for coloring and things like that.

684
01:19:39,116 --> 01:19:51,665
[SPEAKER_25]: But then having specific times in the day when grade grouping does make sense because of developmental needs, things like homework support or things like a group gym game.

685
01:19:52,145 --> 01:19:56,126
[SPEAKER_25]: Oftentimes, we don't want a six-year-old playing the same gym game with a 10-year-old.

686
01:19:56,226 --> 01:20:00,607
[SPEAKER_25]: And so knowing that there would be certain times in the day where we would be separating those groups.

687
01:20:01,027 --> 01:20:07,249
[SPEAKER_25]: But overall, over the course of the day, many of the activities are opened up for those grades.

688
01:20:07,329 --> 01:20:09,950
[SPEAKER_25]: And they're intermixed, having a lot of choice.

689
01:20:10,150 --> 01:20:17,272
[SPEAKER_25]: The real emphasis being here is that there are teachers stationed at all these different spaces where all these different activities are occurring.

690
01:20:17,772 --> 01:20:26,337
[SPEAKER_25]: and that students are being able to opt in and out throughout the day of those spaces and activities, really being driven by their individual interests.

691
01:20:26,737 --> 01:20:37,804
[SPEAKER_25]: Knowing that if I want to spend time outside with my friends, that's great, but if I really want to then go into the art room and do the STEAM project 20 minutes later, that's available to me, and I have that option.

692
01:20:38,484 --> 01:20:43,007
[SPEAKER_25]: And that if I have homework to do, I have a set time on my schedule where I'm supposed to get my homework done.

693
01:20:44,047 --> 01:20:52,992
[SPEAKER_25]: So again, this idea drives this idea of how do you do intermixed or multi-age programming and be able to have student choice be facilitated well.

694
01:20:53,672 --> 01:20:58,494
[SPEAKER_25]: And we do believe, based off of staffing and spaces, that this is very doable for all the programs.

695
01:20:59,215 --> 01:21:05,618
[SPEAKER_25]: The only other thing I would like to highlight for everyone, because this came up as observational data and even with our recommendations,

696
01:21:05,998 --> 01:21:08,839
[SPEAKER_25]: We know that this is still going to be tight staffing.

697
01:21:09,820 --> 01:21:17,223
[SPEAKER_25]: If you look at the first 15 minutes, 15, 20 minutes of the day, you can really see that there's only one space available.

698
01:21:17,943 --> 01:21:22,325
[SPEAKER_25]: And that is, and then the outside there, it's the cafeteria for snack and meeting.

699
01:21:22,725 --> 01:21:23,746
[SPEAKER_25]: and then outside.

700
01:21:24,546 --> 01:21:41,334
[SPEAKER_25]: Because of the contract with para professionals or the contracts that paras have, no matter what, we do foresee that there's still going to be a very tight staffing and very tight student to staff ratios during that time until paras are able to join the program.

701
01:21:41,814 --> 01:21:44,856
[SPEAKER_25]: And so having one central location for check-in

702
01:21:45,296 --> 01:21:58,681
[SPEAKER_25]: where students have a very low-level activity, where it's something like snack and meeting, and then going outside is where you're going to be able to have the safest opportunity to be able to supervise those children until more adults appear.

703
01:21:59,162 --> 01:22:03,743
[SPEAKER_25]: And so that was a very strategic choice in the schedule that we do also recommend for programs going forward.

704
01:22:04,704 --> 01:22:04,964
[SPEAKER_25]: Thank you.

705
01:22:10,807 --> 01:22:15,890
[SPEAKER_06]: So I want to talk next about the kind of financial implications of this model.

706
01:22:17,391 --> 01:22:31,420
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, when we're talking about hiring full-time staff members, we're talking about increasing site coordinators to full-time levels or to an FTE role that does take a financial investment.

707
01:22:34,181 --> 01:22:40,707
[SPEAKER_06]: Working with Medford Public Schools on this is much like how we go about budgeting for our own programs.

708
01:22:41,168 --> 01:22:43,129
[SPEAKER_06]: You're working through the revolving account.

709
01:22:43,670 --> 01:22:45,692
[SPEAKER_06]: The programs need to be able to fund themselves.

710
01:22:47,053 --> 01:22:57,963
[SPEAKER_06]: But we also wanted to make sure that we're, again, approaching this with a level that we're not making a huge ask of the community with very, very large tuition increases.

711
01:22:58,923 --> 01:23:08,832
[SPEAKER_06]: So, the rates that you see here are the after school annual and monthly rates, and we also scoped out camp.

712
01:23:08,892 --> 01:23:12,715
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, that's February and April camp tuition, as well as professional development days.

713
01:23:12,755 --> 01:23:16,778
[SPEAKER_06]: There are two of them per year tuition rates for MPS.

714
01:23:19,520 --> 01:23:27,345
[SPEAKER_06]: I want to point out that, again, the surplus that you see there does appear large, $376,000 surplus.

715
01:23:28,026 --> 01:23:30,327
[SPEAKER_06]: So from that perspective, that news looks great.

716
01:23:31,168 --> 01:23:36,571
[SPEAKER_06]: But I want to flag for all of you that there are a couple of gaps that are not included in that.

717
01:23:37,392 --> 01:23:38,813
[SPEAKER_06]: The first noteworthy gap

718
01:23:39,273 --> 01:23:52,289
[SPEAKER_06]: is that that number does not account for the sliding tuition scale based on household income that Medford Public Schools currently uses and would like to prioritize continuing to use.

719
01:23:53,130 --> 01:23:56,895
[SPEAKER_06]: The impact of those unrealized tuition dollars

720
01:23:57,375 --> 01:24:03,600
[SPEAKER_06]: is not something that we have to kind of bake into our financial model.

721
01:24:04,140 --> 01:24:09,484
[SPEAKER_06]: So we wanted to make sure we were leaving enough space to be able to fund that very high priority.

722
01:24:10,044 --> 01:24:26,336
[SPEAKER_06]: The second piece, which is a much smaller impact overall on budget, is that although we did make a substantial increase to the number of dollars that are spent per pupil, participating pupil, on things like supplies and equipment,

723
01:24:26,996 --> 01:24:29,797
[SPEAKER_06]: a much higher investment than is currently being made.

724
01:24:30,818 --> 01:24:44,224
[SPEAKER_06]: We would, if the budget allowed in that first year, recommend that that managing director be able to make some decisions about one-time investments in capital that would help with equipment to run programs going forward.

725
01:24:44,244 --> 01:24:51,168
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, not as high a priority as making sure the access is there for families that need it, but that is a second priority that we would look at.

726
01:24:54,568 --> 01:24:57,750
[SPEAKER_06]: With that, we can switch slides.

727
01:25:00,171 --> 01:25:03,132
[SPEAKER_06]: So I wanted to, again, take a moment to thank all of you.

728
01:25:03,372 --> 01:25:05,173
[SPEAKER_06]: Actually, I wanted to say one more thing.

729
01:25:05,513 --> 01:25:06,414
[SPEAKER_06]: I neglected a point.

730
01:25:07,975 --> 01:25:16,559
[SPEAKER_06]: Throughout all of this process before I conclude, again, the model we flagged is an area for you all to gain more information.

731
01:25:17,419 --> 01:25:20,623
[SPEAKER_06]: about the programs, particularly for the financial piece.

732
01:25:21,043 --> 01:25:37,139
[SPEAKER_06]: There is a financial tool that we prepared for Dr. Galluzzi and for the new managing director when that person is hired, so that we're not just providing a static model that will fit next year and next year only.

733
01:25:37,619 --> 01:26:03,257
[SPEAKER_06]: But that financial tool, as well as the entire vision, is built so that as changes are needed, so when that second phase of expansion comes around, when there are priorities within the school district that need to also be aligned at after school, there are tools in place to be able to make those changes in an informed way and to be able to play out how those changes will affect programming, both financially and programmatically.

734
01:26:04,737 --> 01:26:08,379
[SPEAKER_06]: Apologies for kind of skipping to the conclusion before I mentioned that point.

735
01:26:09,459 --> 01:26:12,840
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, I wanted to thank all of you to be part of this.

736
01:26:12,860 --> 01:26:14,961
[SPEAKER_06]: This was a wonderful collaboration.

737
01:26:15,921 --> 01:26:18,903
[SPEAKER_06]: For our end, you know, we learned a lot and really,

738
01:26:20,143 --> 01:26:29,625
[SPEAKER_06]: valued working with a group of people that care so deeply about the out-of-school time experience for the families and children.

739
01:26:30,806 --> 01:26:40,508
[SPEAKER_06]: As Suzanne and I said about a year ago, when we started talking about this issue, I said, yes, we run very, very large programs at BASIC.

740
01:26:41,028 --> 01:26:44,109
[SPEAKER_06]: We have a program that serves 400 students at one school.

741
01:26:45,829 --> 01:26:52,573
[SPEAKER_06]: But by and large, and this isn't just in areas of the country that really don't have the resources.

742
01:26:53,174 --> 01:26:58,597
[SPEAKER_06]: This is in the most affluent area in the world, almost.

743
01:26:58,937 --> 01:27:04,601
[SPEAKER_06]: Greater Boston, where you'd think there would be enough resources to make sure this is available for every family.

744
01:27:05,481 --> 01:27:07,983
[SPEAKER_06]: this is a problem in almost every district.

745
01:27:08,323 --> 01:27:10,584
[SPEAKER_06]: So this is not an issue that Medford is facing alone.

746
01:27:11,685 --> 01:27:26,734
[SPEAKER_06]: It's been really wonderful for us to be able to do some work in trying to make that not a major issue for parents because it is something that every community is really struggling to deal with and is going to need to figure out a solution for.

747
01:27:26,894 --> 01:27:31,257
[SPEAKER_06]: So thank you again for inviting us to be part of this process with all of you.

748
01:27:34,200 --> 01:27:34,640
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

749
01:27:36,261 --> 01:27:37,582
[SPEAKER_31]: Are there questions from the committee?

750
01:27:43,186 --> 01:27:43,827
[SPEAKER_31]: Member Rousseau?

751
01:27:46,308 --> 01:27:46,829
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

752
01:27:47,229 --> 01:27:47,549
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

753
01:27:49,831 --> 01:27:55,475
[SPEAKER_21]: Other than the job description for the managing director, was there any recommendations to change the job descriptions for the site directors?

754
01:27:56,192 --> 01:28:04,295
[SPEAKER_06]: Yep, so we prepared site director job descriptions, curriculum specialist job description, and a kindergarten specialist job description.

755
01:28:04,535 --> 01:28:04,855
[SPEAKER_06]: Excellent.

756
01:28:05,015 --> 01:28:06,095
[SPEAKER_21]: You probably said that.

757
01:28:06,135 --> 01:28:06,735
[SPEAKER_21]: You said a lot of things.

758
01:28:06,755 --> 01:28:10,016
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't think I did, but yeah, it's a good ask.

759
01:28:11,417 --> 01:28:18,459
[SPEAKER_21]: Does the budget that was, it's not an actual budget, but does that include the overhead expenses for facilities that we charge the program?

760
01:28:18,499 --> 01:28:19,079
[SPEAKER_21]: It does, yes.

761
01:28:19,139 --> 01:28:19,559
[SPEAKER_21]: Excellent.

762
01:28:20,300 --> 01:28:23,741
[SPEAKER_21]: And other than the ten specialists,

763
01:28:25,045 --> 01:28:30,267
[SPEAKER_21]: Were there additional staff members on the ground that were gonna be required?

764
01:28:30,367 --> 01:28:37,529
[SPEAKER_21]: Because, well, we don't have a factory to make those people.

765
01:28:38,289 --> 01:28:45,931
[SPEAKER_21]: The site director, the recommendation to make them full-time should make a big difference in being able to hire them.

766
01:28:45,951 --> 01:28:47,052
[SPEAKER_21]: I mean, we have them.

767
01:28:48,832 --> 01:28:51,033
[SPEAKER_21]: And the specialists are also full-time.

768
01:28:53,196 --> 01:28:58,043
[SPEAKER_21]: It's the folks that are working three hours a day that concern me.

769
01:28:59,645 --> 01:29:03,151
[SPEAKER_21]: But if we had the same number we have today, would we be able to do this capacity?

770
01:29:03,653 --> 01:29:06,714
[SPEAKER_06]: If we had the same numbers that we had today, we'd be able to do this, yes.

771
01:29:07,054 --> 01:29:07,734
[SPEAKER_06]: Wonderful.

772
01:29:07,754 --> 01:29:12,095
[SPEAKER_06]: We never know from one year to the next who's going to continue in their employment.

773
01:29:12,896 --> 01:29:19,797
[SPEAKER_06]: We're hoping that this is a challenge that every out-of-school-time organization faces.

774
01:29:22,658 --> 01:29:39,901
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to build in structures, and Michael talked a bit about this earlier, where there's some upward mobility throughout the organization so that each role that we're posting and every person that then takes on that role, you're better able to retain them over time as they see that there's a path forward for themselves.

775
01:29:41,542 --> 01:29:47,743
[SPEAKER_06]: But as of the structure as it's created, yes, we can meet all of those with the current staffing.

776
01:29:48,663 --> 01:30:09,661
[SPEAKER_06]: I'll flag, too, that the financial, you know, tool that we provided to Dr. Galussi, we build in roles as part of those expenses so that, you know, as realities happen, you know, we don't really know, and I didn't get into this detail when I talked about the capacity slide, but when we're serving 195 seats,

777
01:30:12,562 --> 01:30:19,965
[SPEAKER_06]: We can make projections about how that group will, you know, kind of select their program experience.

778
01:30:20,125 --> 01:30:26,528
[SPEAKER_06]: You know, you offer currently three different options for families to sign up for either, you know, five days, three days, or two days.

779
01:30:27,128 --> 01:30:30,789
[SPEAKER_06]: Ideally, over time, we build that out to any number.

780
01:30:30,869 --> 01:30:34,050
[SPEAKER_06]: That's how you get the broadest access to programming.

781
01:30:34,110 --> 01:30:36,871
[SPEAKER_06]: If it's a family that needs four days, that's a possibility.

782
01:30:36,891 --> 01:30:38,792
[SPEAKER_06]: If it's a family that needs one day, that's a possibility.

783
01:30:39,272 --> 01:30:54,257
[SPEAKER_06]: So you end up getting, when you increase capacity over time and you increase options for family, you get a, what I like to call, a lower distribution of the selection of days per week, rather than a real high

784
01:30:54,617 --> 01:30:59,303
[SPEAKER_06]: what I like to call high-level distribution, where it's mostly families who are five-day and just jumping it.

785
01:30:59,443 --> 01:31:05,109
[SPEAKER_06]: I wanted to have the program, so I'm gonna take all five days just in case, because I know if I lose it, I'll never get it back.

786
01:31:05,550 --> 01:31:10,376
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're really operating with this high-level distribution now, and you have an even number of staff across days.

787
01:31:10,736 --> 01:31:32,686
[SPEAKER_06]: So we want to build in tools so that as that changes over time, and you're looking for more three-day people or two-day people, you have kind of plug-and-play numbers that you can put in the financial projection to say, okay, I'm replacing this person with this person, or we're hiring somebody because we have 10 more students, and this is the role we need and it's the right number to financially plan for that going forward.

788
01:31:33,567 --> 01:31:33,907
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

789
01:31:33,927 --> 01:31:36,310
[SPEAKER_21]: I have two more questions, but I'll let my colleagues have a shot first.

790
01:31:44,752 --> 01:31:51,398
[SPEAKER_19]: Something that we also would like to recommend, too, is identifying individuals who are currently on the team and giving them prep hours.

791
01:31:51,858 --> 01:32:00,125
[SPEAKER_19]: So, you know, a schedule of noon to six, one to six, so a little bit of planning time based on an interest area and a need.

792
01:32:00,505 --> 01:32:08,912
[SPEAKER_19]: And this is really going to help create those pathways for advancement that Andrew talked about, really motivate individual people, contribute to that culture of initiative.

793
01:32:10,033 --> 01:32:21,498
[SPEAKER_19]: And so that's all under the management of the site director to identify those folks to give them the coaching and the help necessary to plan that activity they might be interested in.

794
01:32:21,878 --> 01:32:28,320
[SPEAKER_19]: So we're confident that those folks exist and we wouldn't have to hire from them but we do want to identify them as quickly as possible.

795
01:32:31,622 --> 01:32:32,122
[SPEAKER_31]: Member Parks.

796
01:32:35,938 --> 01:32:36,319
[SPEAKER_32]: There we go.

797
01:32:36,839 --> 01:32:37,079
[SPEAKER_32]: Sorry.

798
01:32:38,440 --> 01:32:41,022
[SPEAKER_32]: So I just want to say something and then I have a couple of questions.

799
01:32:41,702 --> 01:32:47,886
[SPEAKER_32]: As someone who's been involved kind of from the beginning, I'm really pleased the direction this has gone.

800
01:32:48,566 --> 01:33:04,476
[SPEAKER_32]: And as one of the few on the task force who always had a kid in the after school program, I, you know, my main concerns from the start were scaling up in meaningful ways while keeping the existing programs kind of spark

801
01:33:06,051 --> 01:33:10,434
[SPEAKER_32]: with it and also not having a huge impact on the cost.

802
01:33:11,535 --> 01:33:15,098
[SPEAKER_32]: And I think that you know I'm really thrilled about the concrete improvements.

803
01:33:15,138 --> 01:33:17,961
[SPEAKER_32]: You know we've increased spots at all four elementary schools.

804
01:33:19,061 --> 01:33:26,107
[SPEAKER_32]: We've talked about bringing back the vouchers which I used previously and I didn't like seeing go away.

805
01:33:27,729 --> 01:33:30,491
[SPEAKER_32]: We're making the site coordinator positions full time.

806
01:33:31,333 --> 01:33:32,773
[SPEAKER_32]: so we can retain excellent staff.

807
01:33:32,993 --> 01:33:40,335
[SPEAKER_32]: I personally know that we were about to lose some really great staff members because those were not full-time positions.

808
01:33:41,716 --> 01:33:53,458
[SPEAKER_32]: We're adding specialists for the enhanced programming, and so none of this wouldn't have been possible without, I think, a few steps along the way that I want people to acknowledge.

809
01:33:54,599 --> 01:34:00,640
[SPEAKER_32]: Dr. Galussi's leadership, she, when we came to her, she understood the urgency.

810
01:34:01,729 --> 01:34:04,870
[SPEAKER_32]: of this issue and moved it forward.

811
01:34:04,950 --> 01:34:08,071
[SPEAKER_32]: She was open to all of our early discussions and ideas.

812
01:34:08,971 --> 01:34:12,812
[SPEAKER_32]: And honestly, without her championing this, it would have kind of stalled from the start.

813
01:34:13,352 --> 01:34:13,932
[SPEAKER_32]: So thank you.

814
01:34:14,972 --> 01:34:24,715
[SPEAKER_32]: And then the principals, the site coordinators, the caregivers on the task force, thank you for working together to make this real and holding us accountable to a program

815
01:34:25,238 --> 01:34:31,740
[SPEAKER_32]: that works for Medford, while also at the same time being open to all of the new changes.

816
01:34:32,400 --> 01:34:43,844
[SPEAKER_32]: And then also basic, your support, your expertise, and your willingness to engage in a truly collaborative partnership, which is very different from your standard model, I know.

817
01:34:44,824 --> 01:34:48,986
[SPEAKER_32]: So this was a big kind of risk and a big kind of leap of faith, I think.

818
01:34:49,906 --> 01:34:52,227
[SPEAKER_32]: So that flexibility really made a lot of difference.

819
01:34:53,155 --> 01:34:58,157
[SPEAKER_32]: I have seen their spreadsheet and their financial model.

820
01:34:58,397 --> 01:35:02,079
[SPEAKER_32]: And it's amazing how you can plug it in and play with it.

821
01:35:02,239 --> 01:35:05,440
[SPEAKER_32]: So kudos to them for that.

822
01:35:07,121 --> 01:35:09,361
[SPEAKER_32]: Now moving back, I know we still have a lot of work.

823
01:35:09,622 --> 01:35:10,922
[SPEAKER_32]: And I know the proof is in the pudding.

824
01:35:10,982 --> 01:35:16,724
[SPEAKER_32]: So we are going to hopefully see the results of all of this.

825
01:35:17,485 --> 01:35:18,425
[SPEAKER_32]: A few questions, though.

826
01:35:19,105 --> 01:35:20,146
[SPEAKER_32]: Sibling discount.

827
01:35:21,178 --> 01:35:23,340
[SPEAKER_32]: I could not tell if that was factored in.

828
01:35:23,801 --> 01:35:25,182
[SPEAKER_06]: It's not factored in.

829
01:35:25,523 --> 01:35:26,424
[SPEAKER_06]: No.

830
01:35:26,464 --> 01:35:27,665
[SPEAKER_06]: Right now it's 5 percent.

831
01:35:27,785 --> 01:35:29,347
[SPEAKER_32]: It is currently 5 percent.

832
01:35:29,467 --> 01:35:36,154
[SPEAKER_32]: And do you envision that moving forward or do you not envision that or is that up to the district.

833
01:35:36,295 --> 01:35:38,057
[SPEAKER_06]: I think that's an up to the district question.

834
01:35:38,517 --> 01:35:41,500
[SPEAKER_06]: You know for us my recommendation for you know

835
01:35:43,850 --> 01:35:53,934
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, with the priority being making sure we're increasing capacity and access, I guess is a better way to put it, is that sliding scale for tuition.

836
01:35:54,014 --> 01:36:11,222
[SPEAKER_06]: Because if we're prioritizing what the needs are, and we're talking about families that can't afford programming at all, and we have a limited number of dollars in discounts to provide, my first recommendation would be to look at those families whose households fall into categories that would meet that sliding scale requirement.

837
01:36:11,722 --> 01:36:16,274
[SPEAKER_06]: and to make the 5% sibling discount a second priority to that.

838
01:36:17,176 --> 01:36:19,582
