958
01:48:40,033 --> 01:48:43,779
[SPEAKER_19]: And so I just for a moment wanted to speak to personal experience.

959
01:48:43,819 --> 01:48:50,468
[SPEAKER_19]: So as a site director under this current model I'm the one who owns managing that difficulty in our in our school district in Maynard.

960
01:48:51,730 --> 01:48:55,515
[SPEAKER_19]: And something I'd like to point out is really the scale of that problem.

961
01:48:56,116 --> 01:49:04,743
[SPEAKER_19]: And so I think when we think of the use of space in a building, it's very easy to think that it's utilized every waking minute.

962
01:49:04,763 --> 01:49:11,968
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think the reality is that there is actually, it's much easier to share the space than people anticipate right away.

963
01:49:11,988 --> 01:49:17,032
[SPEAKER_19]: I also think part of the recommendation to increase the capacity of

964
01:49:18,098 --> 01:49:27,182
[SPEAKER_19]: The director and specialist is so that they can be owning that problem and they can come up with a separate plan on those individual days that exist.

965
01:49:27,662 --> 01:49:34,626
[SPEAKER_19]: And so we always prioritize a relationship where we want the school to do, the district to do the things that they want to do.

966
01:49:34,646 --> 01:49:36,226
[SPEAKER_19]: And if there's a basketball program, great.

967
01:49:36,566 --> 01:49:42,029
[SPEAKER_19]: Let's work out that schedule, what time is that going to be in a specific day, what day of the week, and then we'll adjust.

968
01:49:42,710 --> 01:49:48,796
[SPEAKER_19]: And I think the way it ends up playing out is that there's still enough time for each program to get in.

969
01:49:49,596 --> 01:49:50,998
[SPEAKER_19]: There's 180 days in that year.

970
01:49:51,018 --> 01:49:58,606
[SPEAKER_19]: We're not expecting that we have each of those spaces from dismissal until 6, every one of those 180 days.

971
01:49:58,646 --> 01:50:05,352
[SPEAKER_19]: And so I think we've never encountered an issue or a problem with that support staff

972
01:50:07,055 --> 01:50:17,065
[SPEAKER_26]: I think a big thing that we've faced in Medford is that communication and the expectation around who is, you know, when a school is having an art night, what happens?

973
01:50:17,225 --> 01:50:22,891
[SPEAKER_26]: We're taking over the hallways, hanging student art frantically before everyone arrives.

974
01:50:22,951 --> 01:50:25,634
[SPEAKER_26]: So that's where I think it becomes really important.

975
01:50:26,074 --> 01:50:28,035
[SPEAKER_26]: for there to be ownership on specific sites.

976
01:50:28,455 --> 01:50:39,762
[SPEAKER_26]: But I'm also wondering how that interfaces with, you were talking about a coherent vision for the full program, and this actually taps into Member Parks' question around the STEAM specialists.

977
01:50:39,782 --> 01:50:41,563
[SPEAKER_26]: There might not be someone for their site.

978
01:50:41,963 --> 01:50:45,225
[SPEAKER_26]: What opportunity is there to share that expertise?

979
01:50:45,285 --> 01:50:48,407
[SPEAKER_26]: You know, if something fabulous is developed at one site,

980
01:50:49,087 --> 01:51:07,819
[SPEAKER_26]: how do we make sure it gets somewhere else, and that the site, the on-site staff has that training, that planning to say, oh, this is such a great community craft that we're doing, and it's going to look different in different sites, but really that ability to customize, and that comes into the professional development.

981
01:51:07,859 --> 01:51:17,826
[SPEAKER_26]: Professional development is great and fantastic and important, and if you don't build in the time to customize it and tailor it to your students, it doesn't go.

982
01:51:18,446 --> 01:51:19,626
[SPEAKER_28]: to see if there's a potential moment?

983
01:51:19,887 --> 01:51:20,467
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, sure.

984
01:51:20,767 --> 01:51:24,148
[SPEAKER_19]: I would say that that ownership comes from the managing director.

985
01:51:24,428 --> 01:51:30,290
[SPEAKER_19]: And so that person has those site directors at their disposal to be feeding that information up.

986
01:51:31,050 --> 01:51:45,855
[SPEAKER_19]: So if one team specialist is really working on something that's great, as we move into the next phase of this project, that we would recommend that that managing director is having weekly, monthly meetings with their site directors to like, hey, what's going on?

987
01:51:46,075 --> 01:51:47,656
[SPEAKER_19]: Like ear to the ground kind of stuff.

988
01:51:47,956 --> 01:51:54,581
[SPEAKER_26]: I mean, and that's the kind of thing that Dr. Galluzzi has done as superintendent is to try to improve the communication across schools, so.

989
01:51:54,681 --> 01:52:00,705
[SPEAKER_25]: I also wanted to really emphasize the reason why I think having specialists as full-time across sites is so vital.

990
01:52:01,625 --> 01:52:05,388
[SPEAKER_25]: One thing that we've even really implemented is what we call COPs, community of practice.

991
01:52:05,728 --> 01:52:07,770
[SPEAKER_25]: They mean different things in different communities.

992
01:52:08,370 --> 01:52:12,773
[SPEAKER_25]: But for us, it's actually a gathering meeting of individuals with similar positions.

993
01:52:13,213 --> 01:52:19,495
[SPEAKER_25]: So, for instance, our STEM specialists, they meet once a month to be able to share resources and information.

994
01:52:19,956 --> 01:52:40,043
[SPEAKER_25]: And so, you know, I think by being able to move specialists to that full-time position, it allows not just the managing directors to kind of manage up people, but it also allows individuals to work with each other and share resources, so that the MSITUC specialists and other educators who might be interested

995
01:52:40,423 --> 01:52:44,847
[SPEAKER_25]: have an opportunity to talk to the McGlynn specialists and educators and the Roberts.

996
01:52:44,967 --> 01:52:47,929
[SPEAKER_25]: And so it really builds in that time and space to be able to do that.

997
01:52:48,250 --> 01:53:00,980
[SPEAKER_25]: And it first starts with full-time staff, and then as there are other teachers who are interested, building them into being part of that so that resources don't also stay stagnant to one site, but they can be actually shared across the community.

998
01:53:01,000 --> 01:53:01,701
[SPEAKER_26]: Right.

999
01:53:01,781 --> 01:53:03,202
[SPEAKER_26]: And I do wonder about

1000
01:53:04,202 --> 01:53:06,543
[SPEAKER_26]: hiring and being able to fill all of those.

1001
01:53:06,583 --> 01:53:13,927
[SPEAKER_26]: I know, for example, we wanted literacy specialists for the school day, and we couldn't fill all the positions.

1002
01:53:13,967 --> 01:53:20,230
[SPEAKER_26]: And so the thought was one per elementary school, and now we have two across the elementary schools.

1003
01:53:21,390 --> 01:53:28,099
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm wondering if we're going to find ourselves there but I guess the only way you find that out is if you post the job descriptions and you see what happens.

1004
01:53:29,160 --> 01:53:38,211
[SPEAKER_26]: But thinking about whether it makes sense to do some sharing if it's three days at one school and two days at another or something like that I would love to see.

1005
01:53:38,231 --> 01:53:39,293
[SPEAKER_26]: I had.

1006
01:53:41,188 --> 01:53:52,736
[SPEAKER_06]: On that point, as you find that, Erica, you're absolutely always at the mercy of whatever candidates are out there in the hiring environment.

1007
01:53:53,576 --> 01:54:00,200
[SPEAKER_06]: But I will say, at BASIC, we're the only out-of-school-time organization that pays full-time.

1008
01:54:01,041 --> 01:54:04,205
[SPEAKER_06]: And I think that's a big part of what we're trying to do.

1009
01:54:17,203 --> 01:54:31,129
[SPEAKER_06]: Now one of two organizations that offer this, and the fact that it's a district position, I think it automatically elevates the desirability of that over just an organization that is offering something like that.

1010
01:54:31,810 --> 01:54:36,372
[SPEAKER_06]: People look at it as the stability, the upward mobility, all kind of baked into the job.

1011
01:54:37,412 --> 01:54:40,874
[SPEAKER_06]: I think it gives me a lot of confidence that you're gonna find good candidates for this.

1012
01:54:41,412 --> 01:54:46,175
[SPEAKER_26]: I mean, as long as we can afford it, I think that's that school committee ad again.

1013
01:54:46,215 --> 01:54:49,057
[SPEAKER_06]: It's the future of out-of-school time programming.

1014
01:54:49,097 --> 01:54:54,940
[SPEAKER_26]: I mean, and it should, like I said, I came up in this world, museums were- You know, right, you know.

1015
01:54:54,960 --> 01:54:55,360
[SPEAKER_06]: I do.

1016
01:54:55,901 --> 01:55:00,123
[SPEAKER_06]: And you know what it can do for bringing great people into.

1017
01:55:00,143 --> 01:55:05,206
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, you know, can I have any shared colleague who

1018
01:55:06,762 --> 01:55:24,659
[SPEAKER_06]: came into the out-of-school time field not as an education professional, but found it because she found the idea of teaching in that space to be just very exciting and interesting, and then made it her career, especially in greater Boston, a lot of folks like that.

1019
01:55:25,620 --> 01:55:31,224
[SPEAKER_26]: And this program, we still have room for our student assistants and our city year folks who are helping.

1020
01:55:31,264 --> 01:55:32,945
[SPEAKER_26]: They're still in the room.

1021
01:55:32,966 --> 01:55:46,516
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, in fact, I mean, we highlighted a number of times throughout the report how important those folks are and what, you know, an extremely valuable resource you have in both of those categories of employees.

1022
01:55:47,517 --> 01:55:52,902
[SPEAKER_06]: we would go to extreme lengths to ensure that you continue those relationships.

1023
01:55:52,982 --> 01:55:55,544
[SPEAKER_06]: They are a great deal for what you're getting.

1024
01:55:55,644 --> 01:55:57,626
[SPEAKER_06]: Those are fantastic partnerships.

1025
01:56:00,238 --> 01:56:00,598
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay.

1026
01:56:01,439 --> 01:56:07,204
[SPEAKER_26]: You mentioned this in the report that the early pickup model added some seats but didn't necessarily work.

1027
01:56:07,304 --> 01:56:09,145
[SPEAKER_26]: Is there still room for that?

1028
01:56:09,165 --> 01:56:17,632
[SPEAKER_26]: Because we did hear from some people that, for example, teachers in other districts who said, I just need a little more coverage.

1029
01:56:18,132 --> 01:56:23,696
[SPEAKER_26]: And it sounds like it didn't, that the staffing wasn't necessarily scaled to match it.

1030
01:56:23,716 --> 01:56:24,777
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you want to talk about that, Annie?

1031
01:56:24,917 --> 01:56:25,017
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1032
01:56:25,098 --> 01:56:27,159
[SPEAKER_25]: Do you want me to talk about what the survey said?

1033
01:56:29,721 --> 01:56:31,922
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm happy to talk about it, but I know you would.

1034
01:56:32,102 --> 01:56:43,766
[SPEAKER_25]: I will say, from who we spoke to, I can at least comment from the surveying that we had and going extensively through the survey data, there were some families that reported that the 4 p.m.

1035
01:56:44,086 --> 01:56:46,266
[SPEAKER_25]: works perfectly for their schedule and that they liked it.

1036
01:56:47,187 --> 01:56:53,989
[SPEAKER_25]: It was such a small percentage overall that it didn't really reflect the overall experience.

1037
01:56:54,649 --> 01:56:59,754
[SPEAKER_25]: I truly, it was about three or four responses out of 395.

1038
01:57:00,515 --> 01:57:05,259
[SPEAKER_25]: So it really didn't really, as from what we collected, didn't reflect the overall experience.

1039
01:57:05,800 --> 01:57:10,144
[SPEAKER_25]: And then Michael can actually talk a little bit more about what we observed as far as the 4 p.m.

1040
01:57:10,184 --> 01:57:13,847
[SPEAKER_25]: structure and kind of what we think is better overall programmatically.

1041
01:57:14,808 --> 01:57:17,210
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, I think the intended goal of the 4 p.m.

1042
01:57:17,250 --> 01:57:23,656
[SPEAKER_19]: pickup was to be able to bring in different staff, transparently for cheaper, someone who would just extend another hour of their day.

1043
01:57:24,116 --> 01:57:26,839
[SPEAKER_19]: And it didn't seem like it had met that intended goal.

1044
01:57:27,439 --> 01:57:31,402
[SPEAKER_19]: It's really difficult to find that kind of individual.

1045
01:57:32,824 --> 01:57:42,552
[SPEAKER_19]: The other thing we really observed is that the schedule of after school was then structured around a limited number of students who had to get picked up at 4 o'clock.

1046
01:57:42,872 --> 01:57:45,575
[SPEAKER_19]: So the schedule was built on that dispensal time.

1047
01:57:45,915 --> 01:57:54,483
[SPEAKER_19]: So you had students the majority of students really at that point in one room doing an unpreferred activity when they could be spending their time elsewhere.

1048
01:57:54,964 --> 01:57:57,046
[SPEAKER_19]: And so that on top of it.

1049
01:57:58,227 --> 01:58:04,110
[SPEAKER_19]: just being a bigger administrative burden for folks to keep track of who's being picked up at four.

1050
01:58:04,911 --> 01:58:12,875
[SPEAKER_19]: Our perspective was that it wasn't worth it really, even though it would benefit teachers specifically who just need that little bit of time.

1051
01:58:13,736 --> 01:58:16,997
[SPEAKER_19]: But that it doesn't support the growth that we're really trying to achieve here.

1052
01:58:17,718 --> 01:58:24,722
[SPEAKER_26]: And I think that highlights the aspect here that we're not just looking for a place to house children for a few hours.

1053
01:58:24,742 --> 01:58:26,002
[SPEAKER_26]: We're looking to have really

1054
01:58:27,766 --> 01:58:30,249
[SPEAKER_26]: enriching positive experiences.

1055
01:58:30,689 --> 01:58:46,004
[SPEAKER_26]: So sorry, I know I'm taking up a lot of time, but I had a big question, which is what does integration with the school and our students who require services and special needs, how do they thrive in this program as well?

1056
01:58:46,623 --> 01:58:53,487
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, so we've had conversations about that specifically and about kind of the difference in our experience from district to district.

1057
01:58:53,947 --> 01:58:59,090
[SPEAKER_19]: I'd highlight and make a pitch really for kind of the model that Maynard uses.

1058
01:58:59,991 --> 01:59:02,912
[SPEAKER_19]: So really their reading of Title IX is such that

1059
01:59:04,462 --> 01:59:13,388
[SPEAKER_19]: any program that's operating out of their buildings, whatever service is being granted to that student should be extended to after school as well.

1060
01:59:13,868 --> 01:59:14,448
[SPEAKER_28]: Absolutely.

1061
01:59:14,468 --> 01:59:16,810
[SPEAKER_19]: That's how they run it.

1062
01:59:16,830 --> 01:59:25,035
[SPEAKER_19]: So we work collaboratively with that school district to hire a one-on-one if it's necessary for that individual student.

1063
01:59:25,375 --> 01:59:28,978
[SPEAKER_19]: With that question, I think that's where my mind goes with the kinds of services.

1064
01:59:29,938 --> 01:59:33,861
[SPEAKER_26]: And making sure that this financial model that we can support

1065
01:59:35,203 --> 01:59:36,384
[SPEAKER_26]: those students in this.

1066
01:59:37,164 --> 01:59:44,149
[SPEAKER_19]: So we wouldn't have built that in specifically but I think there would be some space for it within that surplus.

1067
01:59:44,169 --> 01:59:46,190
[SPEAKER_19]: I wouldn't give you any guaranteed number.

1068
01:59:46,210 --> 01:59:52,215
[SPEAKER_19]: The other thing I would really highlight though as a benefit of full time staff is

1069
01:59:53,015 --> 02:00:06,369
[SPEAKER_19]: being able to create behavior plans for those students, maybe on a 504, or who might have a specific need or accommodation that doesn't necessarily rise to the level of a one-on-one.

1070
02:00:06,769 --> 02:00:08,071
[SPEAKER_19]: You can imagine students who

1071
02:00:08,631 --> 02:00:13,373
[SPEAKER_19]: would be perfectly capable of participating in this kind of program, but just a little bit extra of help.

1072
02:00:13,873 --> 02:00:30,340
[SPEAKER_19]: And so that daily staff meeting, a specialist who's designing curriculum with those students, who can take into consideration those students in adjusting their lesson plan, or recommend to a site director a specific example from my program is a student who doesn't have the use of one of their arms.

1073
02:00:30,820 --> 02:00:37,022
[SPEAKER_19]: So we purchased specialized scissors for them so they could continue to do the art projects that they wanted to do.

1074
02:00:38,543 --> 02:01:02,555
[SPEAKER_19]: So a lot of those benefits or those recommendations really have additional benefits to welcoming those types of students and making it easier as opposed to a site coordinator who's coming in at 2.30, you know, 2 o'clock every day and needs to spend 25 minutes on making sure that the attendance is done as opposed to, you know, a few hours a day being like, okay, well, who's this student and what can we do as a team?

1075
02:01:02,895 --> 02:01:04,496
[SPEAKER_19]: Within our resources are ready to accommodate.

1076
02:01:06,213 --> 02:01:10,894
[SPEAKER_26]: So I just hope that will be part of the hiring conversation around these folks.

1077
02:01:10,914 --> 02:01:13,735
[SPEAKER_26]: And then the very last thing I wanted to... Could I just point of... Yeah.

1078
02:01:14,115 --> 02:01:15,556
[SPEAKER_14]: I just want to make one point to that.

1079
02:01:16,616 --> 02:01:25,259
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you, Michael, because I think the piece of the position being full-time is very critical because the managing... Excuse me.

1080
02:01:25,869 --> 02:01:32,130
[SPEAKER_14]: the site director will be able to have conversations with school-based teams and the principal.

1081
02:01:32,391 --> 02:01:40,132
[SPEAKER_14]: And so I do think that these are individual conversations that have to be made in order to create the support that's needed.

1082
02:01:41,253 --> 02:01:42,873
[SPEAKER_14]: 504s are written for settings.

1083
02:01:43,533 --> 02:01:52,355
[SPEAKER_14]: So there are ways in which you can either create another 504 or add on accommodations that are appropriate for extended school day programs.

1084
02:01:52,875 --> 02:01:54,076
[SPEAKER_14]: It's the same for IEPs.

1085
02:01:54,276 --> 02:01:55,176
[SPEAKER_14]: I just cannot

1086
02:01:56,096 --> 02:01:57,417
[SPEAKER_14]: be necessarily mirrored.

1087
02:01:57,617 --> 02:02:03,760
[SPEAKER_14]: So there are staff that are not present in afterschool that are there during the school day.

1088
02:02:03,820 --> 02:02:17,327
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think individual conversations with families so that we can be very clear about what are the reasonable accommodations that we can provide so that students are able to be supported in afterschool care is 100% the priority.

1089
02:02:17,807 --> 02:02:22,869
[SPEAKER_14]: But we have to be very transparent that afterschool is not housed with nurses or

1090
02:02:24,050 --> 02:02:27,593
[SPEAKER_14]: school adjustment counselors, or behaviorists, or BCBAs.

1091
02:02:27,673 --> 02:02:48,430
[SPEAKER_14]: So all of those, if any of those positions are required, then that's the one-to-one conversations that have to occur between the site director, the school itself, whatever the team of representation that is, and the caregivers, so that we can create the plan that's needed to support the students to the best of our ability.

1092
02:02:49,518 --> 02:02:57,022
[SPEAKER_19]: I, myself, am involved in a lot of those conversations with BCBAs, with school adjustment counselors, because I work in the building itself.

1093
02:02:57,082 --> 02:02:58,643
[SPEAKER_19]: They can pop by my office.

1094
02:02:58,683 --> 02:02:59,284
[SPEAKER_19]: I can go by them.

1095
02:02:59,304 --> 02:03:03,006
[SPEAKER_19]: I'm like, hey, we can collaborate on those kiddos.

1096
02:03:03,066 --> 02:03:04,126
[SPEAKER_26]: In all our spare time, right?

1097
02:03:04,507 --> 02:03:05,707
[SPEAKER_19]: I mean, you've got to make it work, right?

1098
02:03:05,747 --> 02:03:06,388
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, exactly.

1099
02:03:06,408 --> 02:03:07,868
[SPEAKER_19]: We're supporting the same children.

1100
02:03:08,029 --> 02:03:08,949
[SPEAKER_19]: We're here for the kids.

1101
02:03:09,009 --> 02:03:11,430
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, we do what we can.

1102
02:03:11,450 --> 02:03:14,692
[SPEAKER_19]: If a specific service or someone couldn't be hired.

1103
02:03:15,233 --> 02:03:17,594
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, and just making sure that's not an afterthought.

1104
02:03:19,914 --> 02:03:21,635
[SPEAKER_26]: This program needs to be open for all.

1105
02:03:22,175 --> 02:03:36,742
[SPEAKER_26]: So then the last thing I will just flag is that we are in the midst of another task force looking at moving fifth grade out of the elementary schools and so thinking about not now not today but just recognizing that

1106
02:03:36,982 --> 02:03:40,125
[SPEAKER_26]: that the elementary school composition may be changing.

1107
02:03:40,566 --> 02:03:44,290
[SPEAKER_26]: We've already had lots of conversations, so that will continue.

1108
02:03:44,350 --> 02:03:44,570
[SPEAKER_26]: Yes.

1109
02:03:44,951 --> 02:03:51,137
[SPEAKER_26]: And because I think one of the things I've heard is that we want to retain some of that elementary school

1110
02:03:52,751 --> 02:04:08,126
[SPEAKER_26]: deep I love the deep learning that's getting built in rather than worksheets and and and coloring like real art projects not just coloring and making sure that that is available to our fifth and sixth graders when if and when we we shift there.

1111
02:04:08,346 --> 02:04:08,526
[SPEAKER_26]: All right.

1112
02:04:08,726 --> 02:04:10,168
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm going to turn off my microphone.

1113
02:04:10,208 --> 02:04:11,329
[SPEAKER_26]: I see lots of other lights.

1114
02:04:11,629 --> 02:04:13,451
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you for indulging my questions.

1115
02:04:15,012 --> 02:04:15,633
[SPEAKER_31]: Member Lopate.

1116
02:04:18,807 --> 02:04:19,227
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1117
02:04:19,367 --> 02:04:19,848
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you so much.

1118
02:04:19,868 --> 02:04:20,668
[SPEAKER_07]: This is wonderful.

1119
02:04:21,128 --> 02:04:22,169
[SPEAKER_07]: A couple quick questions.

1120
02:04:22,409 --> 02:04:30,813
[SPEAKER_07]: So one of the things that was mentioned earlier is that families cited the need for more transparency regarding communication, the wait list system, just the process in general.

1121
02:04:32,314 --> 02:04:34,996
[SPEAKER_07]: How are we going to ensure, I think, overall clear communication?

1122
02:04:35,356 --> 02:04:39,898
[SPEAKER_07]: I know that a lot of the time it's a timing thing more than anything else, understanding where they fall in the general order.

1123
02:04:40,759 --> 02:04:43,400
[SPEAKER_07]: So can we talk a little bit about what that looks like going forward?

1124
02:04:46,608 --> 02:04:51,438
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah, so I think to get into the weeds a little bit, I think...

1125
02:04:53,091 --> 02:04:57,635
[SPEAKER_19]: What we're really recommending is, I think, to what you're saying, is the timing of things.

1126
02:04:57,715 --> 02:05:01,959
[SPEAKER_19]: And there was a lot of unclear responses in the way that information was flowing out.

1127
02:05:02,019 --> 02:05:11,348
[SPEAKER_19]: And so part of the steps that we've done already in collaboration with the communications director here at Medford is to give as much information ahead of time as possible.

1128
02:05:11,648 --> 02:05:15,192
[SPEAKER_19]: So it's already been clearly communicated when that registration window is going to be.

1129
02:05:16,293 --> 02:05:18,475
[SPEAKER_19]: At the same time, we do have to protect

1130
02:05:19,215 --> 02:05:23,197
[SPEAKER_19]: the ability to make flexible registration decisions.

1131
02:05:23,677 --> 02:05:41,665
[SPEAKER_19]: And so part of some of our conversations have been moving away from that waitlist pool and more to a ranked order, but one in which that provides some flexibility and gives a full registration picture before students are necessarily pulled off of a waitlist.

1132
02:05:41,805 --> 02:05:45,167
[SPEAKER_19]: So what I mean by that is you can imagine a scenario where

1133
02:05:45,767 --> 02:05:52,390
[SPEAKER_19]: Maybe there's 60 kindergartners in an individual school year that registered, but only 10 fifth graders.

1134
02:05:52,810 --> 02:06:03,915
[SPEAKER_19]: So we have enough total resources to accommodate that, and we can plan ahead of time once we have that full registration picture of shifting over staff to open up a second kindergarten classroom.

1135
02:06:04,896 --> 02:06:10,598
[SPEAKER_19]: But that could lead to a scenario where that ranked order is adjusted in some way based on grade, right?

1136
02:06:14,420 --> 02:06:23,644
[SPEAKER_19]: One student might have registered first, but where we're going to distribute our resources is such that they might not be pulled off right away.

1137
02:06:23,664 --> 02:06:25,504
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't know, Andrew, if you want to clarify that.

1138
02:06:25,524 --> 02:06:28,065
[SPEAKER_19]: I hope I'm painting a clear picture.

1139
02:06:28,085 --> 02:06:29,806
[SPEAKER_19]: Yeah.

1140
02:06:29,866 --> 02:06:37,829
[SPEAKER_06]: I think the only piece I would add to that in kind of working through this strategy and the conversations that we've had so far are that

1141
02:06:38,950 --> 02:06:41,192
[SPEAKER_06]: We want to make sure we're being as transparent as possible.

1142
02:06:41,712 --> 02:06:46,715
[SPEAKER_06]: And we also want to be really strategic about how, about sharing information.

1143
02:06:46,735 --> 02:06:49,517
[SPEAKER_06]: Sorry, am I causing feedback there?

1144
02:06:50,457 --> 02:06:58,783
[SPEAKER_06]: About sharing the information in a way that parents understand that here are our priorities

1145
02:06:59,663 --> 02:07:02,184
[SPEAKER_06]: This is how we're managing the overall list.

1146
02:07:02,244 --> 02:07:20,088
[SPEAKER_06]: They understand that there is a structure and a strategy to ensure fairness and try to maximize the number of participants, but also trying to, but not getting in the weeds of it's, you know, it's this particular system and you're, you know, third on the overall wait list, but that, but also,

1147
02:07:20,808 --> 02:07:25,474
[SPEAKER_06]: you know, asterisk fifth when it comes to kindergarten, because if this happens, that happens.

1148
02:07:26,235 --> 02:07:28,438
[SPEAKER_06]: We're just not, you know, something that parents can understand.

1149
02:07:28,458 --> 02:07:35,628
[SPEAKER_06]: So if we're ahead always of this communication strategy, so telling folks early on, you know, for next year particularly,

1150
02:07:36,368 --> 02:07:41,391
[SPEAKER_06]: We did a lot of work this year to increase the number of seats that are available.

1151
02:07:41,772 --> 02:07:47,675
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't think it's going to completely resolve the problem, but we're hoping within the next two years that it completely resolves the problem.

1152
02:07:47,695 --> 02:07:58,922
[SPEAKER_06]: But for next year, we know that whatever the X number of total seats are going to be made available, and we're going to open registration on X date.

1153
02:07:59,662 --> 02:08:11,733
[SPEAKER_06]: and communicate to families that they're in if we know they're in by Y date and be able to make continued decisions about the wait list by Z date.

1154
02:08:12,073 --> 02:08:19,420
[SPEAKER_06]: So that people understand the flow and they understand the strategy even if at the very beginning I don't get spit out a number

1155
02:08:20,060 --> 02:08:23,684
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, you know, you're seventh on the wait list as soon as I register.

1156
02:08:24,104 --> 02:08:30,591
[SPEAKER_06]: You know that there's a process that puts fairness as the highest value.

1157
02:08:31,632 --> 02:08:38,939
[SPEAKER_06]: And that person, that managing director who we're hiring to lead that communication strategy is someone I can reach out to.

1158
02:08:39,660 --> 02:08:51,703
[SPEAKER_06]: that fully understands and can talk through my individual question in a way that we just can't communicate broadly and that would apply to every single student in Medford Public Schools.

1159
02:08:51,723 --> 02:08:52,443
[SPEAKER_06]: Does that make sense?

1160
02:08:52,523 --> 02:08:52,683
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1161
02:08:52,863 --> 02:08:53,443
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you so much.

1162
02:08:53,483 --> 02:08:54,183
[SPEAKER_06]: Sure.

1163
02:08:54,323 --> 02:08:58,204
[SPEAKER_14]: Point of information too, just so we're aware of the X dates.

1164
02:08:59,365 --> 02:09:06,326
[SPEAKER_14]: Tomorrow there is, we're holding a meeting so that we can explain this, what's happening here to the community.

1165
02:09:06,406 --> 02:09:08,687
[SPEAKER_14]: So there is that presentation to the community.

1166
02:09:09,627 --> 02:09:15,533
[SPEAKER_14]: Wednesday, May 6th, the registration for all MPS afterschool lottery will open.

1167
02:09:16,954 --> 02:09:28,265
[SPEAKER_14]: The re-enrollment date for current Medford afterschool families, so something went out to all the current families that are served through the afterschool program.

1168
02:09:28,565 --> 02:09:32,028
[SPEAKER_14]: They've already received a survey to see if they are returning and interested.

1169
02:09:32,448 --> 02:09:33,549
[SPEAKER_14]: That due date is May 12th.

1170
02:09:34,997 --> 02:09:39,641
[SPEAKER_14]: Monday, May 16th, the registration for the lottery will close.

1171
02:09:40,141 --> 02:09:42,463
[SPEAKER_14]: And then we will run a lottery on the 19th.

1172
02:09:43,003 --> 02:09:54,992
[SPEAKER_14]: And so I do have to say that communications director Will Pippicelli has and is doing a fabulous job facilitating a lot and all of the communication.

