1275
02:20:07,132 --> 02:20:15,779
[SPEAKER_20]: Melrose or in Boston or in Chelsea or like other leadership roles that are non-academic or non-school related.

1276
02:20:15,799 --> 02:20:16,959
[SPEAKER_20]: Do you get my question?

1277
02:20:17,120 --> 02:20:19,221
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm sorry, I didn't understand the first part of the question.

1278
02:20:19,261 --> 02:20:21,523
[SPEAKER_06]: Were you saying for the new positions that are being hired?

1279
02:20:22,143 --> 02:20:25,446
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, for the new leadership position of the whole thing.

1280
02:20:26,707 --> 02:20:26,847
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1281
02:20:27,967 --> 02:20:38,818
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, so for that process, that hiring process, you know, Medford Public Schools has their own processes for posting positions and fielding inquiries from interested folks.

1282
02:20:38,939 --> 02:20:43,784
[SPEAKER_06]: So, I mean, they could come from anywhere, and I imagine they will.

1283
02:20:43,804 --> 02:20:45,105
[SPEAKER_06]: I think it's a very competitive position.

1284
02:20:53,194 --> 02:20:59,037
[SPEAKER_20]: What would you do if a family could not afford the financial compensation for the program?

1285
02:20:59,297 --> 02:21:03,759
[SPEAKER_20]: There are a lot of households that are not financially stable to make that money come in.

1286
02:21:05,837 --> 02:21:12,181
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, your question was, what about the family that can't afford the tuition?

1287
02:21:13,161 --> 02:21:26,849
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, unfortunately, this issue goes hand-in-hand with one of the pieces that we talked about earlier, the struggles in the field of out-of-school time in the United States right now.

1288
02:21:26,949 --> 02:21:28,811
[SPEAKER_06]: Again, this is not just a greater Boston problem.

1289
02:21:28,831 --> 02:21:34,374
[SPEAKER_06]: In fact, it's a lesser problem in greater Boston than it is in most communities around this country.

1290
02:21:34,882 --> 02:21:51,818
[SPEAKER_06]: On the one hand, you have the difficulty in finding folks who, in most cases, are able to work a job that is 20 hours a week and that not being a living wage, and that's a difficulty in being able to provide the programming that's available.

1291
02:21:52,138 --> 02:21:53,920
[SPEAKER_06]: And on the other side, to address your question,

1292
02:21:54,932 --> 02:21:59,653
[SPEAKER_06]: It's becoming an extraordinarily high expense for families.

1293
02:22:01,013 --> 02:22:09,575
[SPEAKER_06]: And it is a very challenging issue that is felt very acutely for any family that can't afford it.

1294
02:22:09,715 --> 02:22:16,017
[SPEAKER_06]: I think, luckily, in Medford, we have the history of using the sliding tuition scale.

1295
02:22:18,057 --> 02:22:44,996
[SPEAKER_06]: Looking into also, as we flagged earlier, being able to, again, accept state vouchers, because that is a very well-funded resource that Massachusetts has provided for a long, long time, but since COVID and the accompanying rescue plan got bolstered with more funding, pulling a lot more families off those wait lists, and making the state vouchers a really wonderful resource to provide.

1296
02:22:46,137 --> 02:22:50,480
[SPEAKER_06]: a really scaled subsidy for families that need it.

1297
02:22:50,520 --> 02:22:56,766
[SPEAKER_06]: So between those two tools, I'm hopeful that we're able to meet the needs of every family.

1298
02:22:56,786 --> 02:23:07,755
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, not to say that any family, even if a family that is quite comfortable, the cost of programming, as we saw in numbers, is rising all the time.

1299
02:23:07,775 --> 02:23:10,557
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, just the fact of the expenses that are involved.

1300
02:23:14,643 --> 02:23:19,185
[SPEAKER_29]: Oh, we, me and Christine have a couple of, a decent few questions as well.

1301
02:23:19,505 --> 02:23:19,706
[SPEAKER_29]: I know.

1302
02:23:19,746 --> 02:23:20,026
[SPEAKER_29]: Understood.

1303
02:23:20,066 --> 02:23:20,586
[SPEAKER_29]: If that's possible.

1304
02:23:20,606 --> 02:23:20,966
[SPEAKER_29]: Understood.

1305
02:23:20,986 --> 02:23:21,967
[SPEAKER_30]: You can go ahead, Member Russell.

1306
02:23:21,987 --> 02:23:22,227
[SPEAKER_30]: That's fine.

1307
02:23:22,247 --> 02:23:22,967
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

1308
02:23:23,747 --> 02:23:27,709
[SPEAKER_21]: The reason we got rid of the vouchers, has that changed?

1309
02:23:27,829 --> 02:23:34,633
[SPEAKER_21]: Because the problem we had with the vouchers was that, short of having a PhD, you really couldn't finish the process.

1310
02:23:35,553 --> 02:23:39,495
[SPEAKER_21]: There are vast numbers of people who absolutely are eligible.

1311
02:23:39,955 --> 02:23:42,277
[SPEAKER_21]: and cannot get through the process to get a voucher.

1312
02:23:42,357 --> 02:23:51,425
[SPEAKER_21]: So we felt access was far more important than standing on, hey, there's a state program, but like a lot of state programs, they're not actually accessible.

1313
02:23:51,986 --> 02:23:53,948
[SPEAKER_21]: So have they actually fixed that process?

1314
02:23:54,028 --> 02:23:57,491
[SPEAKER_21]: Because if they haven't, I'm very much opposed to vouchers.

1315
02:23:57,531 --> 02:24:05,918
[SPEAKER_21]: We had a very robust conversation when we got rid of them, and I know it's free money, but it's only free money for those that can actually figure out how to get through the process.

1316
02:24:07,419 --> 02:24:13,281
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's a detail we haven't talked out or we've talked a little bit about but not fully fleshed out.

1317
02:24:13,821 --> 02:24:17,982
[SPEAKER_06]: I would recommend a model like that which we use at BASIC.

1318
02:24:18,062 --> 02:24:24,344
[SPEAKER_06]: So part of our tuition assist, our private tuition assist, which again is very similar to what you would have in a sliding scale.

1319
02:24:24,404 --> 02:24:33,366
[SPEAKER_06]: So a family demonstrates need based on their circumstances and you have a number of discounts that you can give.

1320
02:24:34,546 --> 02:24:39,488
[SPEAKER_06]: that, you know, make it more affordable for that family based on their household income and their family size.

1321
02:24:39,788 --> 02:24:56,653
[SPEAKER_06]: But the first step in our process for applying for our assistance is make that first inquiry for a state voucher, to basically get on the list and start the communication, so that they can move forward with a sliding scale from the district

1322
02:24:57,676 --> 02:25:03,220
[SPEAKER_06]: And for us, it's from BASIC, while they work through that process to obtain a voucher.

1323
02:25:03,420 --> 02:25:09,685
[SPEAKER_06]: Because you're right, it is a difficult process, and it can, again, even though they got rid of the wait list a number of years ago following COVID.

1324
02:25:11,316 --> 02:25:12,437
[SPEAKER_06]: there are wait lists again.

1325
02:25:12,677 --> 02:25:14,599
[SPEAKER_06]: So it can't be your one solution.

1326
02:25:14,719 --> 02:25:15,480
[SPEAKER_06]: So it's a yes and.

1327
02:25:15,900 --> 02:25:16,921
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, so it's a yes and.

1328
02:25:17,201 --> 02:25:34,855
[SPEAKER_06]: But I would say, I would recommend, it depends on the, the vouchers come from the state and then they're sent to these different programs, these different organizations that facilitate the vouchers through a voucher counselor who works individually with the family.

1329
02:25:35,136 --> 02:25:36,457
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're a little bit at the,

1330
02:25:37,357 --> 02:25:39,098
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not going to get into that.

1331
02:25:39,338 --> 02:25:40,599
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not going to get into that.

1332
02:25:40,619 --> 02:25:42,219
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm not going to get into that.

