02:34:23,563 --> 02:34:26,465
[SPEAKER_20]: How much effort did you try to put in to get that request?

1430
02:34:32,134 --> 02:34:35,478
[SPEAKER_25]: As I stated earlier, we did not get a chance to interview students.

1431
02:34:35,839 --> 02:34:39,023
[SPEAKER_25]: Our priority was to really observe the kind of programmatic structure.

1432
02:34:39,944 --> 02:34:46,453
[SPEAKER_25]: And we used the interviews as almost like an expansion of the landscape survey to really kind of dig deeper.

1433
02:34:46,573 --> 02:34:48,977
[SPEAKER_25]: So the interviews really allowed us

1434
02:34:49,437 --> 02:34:54,399
[SPEAKER_25]: to understand what we were seeing and what we saw in survey data a bit further.

1435
02:34:55,199 --> 02:35:00,261
[SPEAKER_25]: And so the interviews, again, really, again, the amount that we were able to do was just about time.

1436
02:35:00,321 --> 02:35:02,742
[SPEAKER_25]: As you see, we did about 20 interviews.

1437
02:35:03,482 --> 02:35:07,724
[SPEAKER_25]: And so we had to really narrow down how many family interviews we could actually do.

1438
02:35:07,824 --> 02:35:12,286
[SPEAKER_25]: But we really tried to get a perspective of internal and external families.

1439
02:35:12,646 --> 02:35:17,508
[SPEAKER_25]: Internal being families that have kids in the programs currently, and then external being families

1440
02:35:18,190 --> 02:35:21,486
[SPEAKER_25]: who unfortunately have been waitlisted and haven't been able to get their kids in yet.

1441
02:35:29,609 --> 02:35:42,661
[SPEAKER_22]: Given that a lot of these gaps in the data is based on a timing deadline and also given that we're probably going to be restructuring this in future years, this is kind of like a base level.

1442
02:35:42,941 --> 02:35:51,028
[SPEAKER_22]: I'm guessing you're going to do a more in-depth look in the coming years as we're sort of expanding this further.

1443
02:35:55,393 --> 02:35:56,753
[SPEAKER_14]: I just, I would like to answer that one.

1444
02:35:57,434 --> 02:36:05,495
[SPEAKER_14]: So I started the meeting with some framing just because there was significant need for us to do, to increase this.

1445
02:36:06,235 --> 02:36:13,776
[SPEAKER_14]: So BASIC has spent an exorbitant amount of time working with our current staff, working with our task force.

1446
02:36:14,457 --> 02:36:19,878
[SPEAKER_14]: So this is not necessarily a continuation of audit and vetting.

1447
02:36:20,038 --> 02:36:21,258
[SPEAKER_14]: What is the next phase?

1448
02:36:22,418 --> 02:36:26,401
[SPEAKER_14]: is they are going to be with us, helping us along the way.

1449
02:36:27,041 --> 02:36:41,530
[SPEAKER_14]: So the next phase is going to be training and professional development for our staff so that we're able to handle the increased capacity and the changes in the format of how afterschool is run.

1450
02:36:42,030 --> 02:36:51,036
[SPEAKER_14]: So BASIC isn't going away, and they're going to be with us for training and professional development and kind of like boots on the ground,

1451
02:36:52,376 --> 02:37:00,919
[SPEAKER_14]: Kind of some on-site assistance as we go to make sure especially those new roles have the support that they need at each building.

1452
02:37:00,979 --> 02:37:02,299
[SPEAKER_14]: But I just want to make that clear.

1453
02:37:04,220 --> 02:37:05,961
[SPEAKER_14]: We're not doing another audit.

1454
02:37:06,361 --> 02:37:06,941
[SPEAKER_14]: That part's done.

1455
02:37:16,584 --> 02:37:31,292
[SPEAKER_29]: One of the other concerns that I sort of had is that I know that we've had, you said around 100,000 in lost revenue from from the sliding, sliding tuition scale.

1456
02:37:32,692 --> 02:37:34,974
[SPEAKER_29]: That is, of course, an absolute value.

1457
02:37:34,994 --> 02:37:36,915
[SPEAKER_29]: Like, it's not a percentage.

1458
02:37:37,455 --> 02:37:41,958
[SPEAKER_29]: And we are, of course, increasing enrollment drastically, so I expect that number to increase.

1459
02:37:43,398 --> 02:37:51,543
[SPEAKER_29]: But we have about 300,000 or 300, you know, 375,000 budget surplus.

1460
02:37:52,023 --> 02:37:56,466
[SPEAKER_29]: So I assume, you know, we're pretty drastically increasing enrollment here, which is amazing.

1461
02:37:57,066 --> 02:37:59,528
[SPEAKER_29]: But it's also going to sort of eat into our budget surplus.

1462
02:37:59,568 --> 02:38:03,510
[SPEAKER_29]: I know that we have some other things that contribute to that.

1463
02:38:04,471 --> 02:38:09,594
[SPEAKER_29]: I'm sure you balanced it correctly because, you know, you've been in this space for a while.

1464
02:38:10,114 --> 02:38:12,236
[SPEAKER_29]: Can you maybe expand on that just a little bit?

1465
02:38:12,396 --> 02:38:17,160
[SPEAKER_06]: But I don't have a significant concern there.

1466
02:38:17,200 --> 02:38:18,021
[SPEAKER_06]: Sure.

1467
02:38:18,962 --> 02:38:19,122
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

1468
02:38:19,222 --> 02:38:31,352
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, we didn't use that $138,000, I think that was the number that Dr. Galussi mentioned a few moments ago, as a previous expense for the district in coming up with that $375,000 number.

1469
02:38:31,372 --> 02:38:31,632
[SPEAKER_06]: I think it's

1470
02:38:37,557 --> 02:38:52,645
[SPEAKER_06]: It's right in the, I wouldn't say center of the bullseye of what I expected, but it is, you know, from a, from like a, how large, you know, the number, the size of the number is comparable to what I was expecting.

1471
02:38:53,426 --> 02:39:00,915
[SPEAKER_06]: And given that we're increasing the number of spots available, we have to assume that that number overall is going to increase.

1472
02:39:02,638 --> 02:39:07,624
[SPEAKER_06]: What we never know with something like a sliding scale is who are those individual folks who are walking in the door.

1473
02:39:07,744 --> 02:39:09,767
[SPEAKER_06]: So our priority for creating that

1474
02:39:11,020 --> 02:39:26,372
[SPEAKER_06]: a financial tool that can help us understand what tuition to set, so we understand how much revenue is coming in, and say we want to make sure we have enough space for these major investments that we don't have a figure for.

1475
02:39:27,073 --> 02:39:38,221
[SPEAKER_06]: And across the board, for every step that we took in this development of the financial tool, we tried to take what you could either call the most conservative or

1476
02:39:39,218 --> 02:39:45,882
[SPEAKER_06]: kind of like least advantageous scenario into account and use that as the baseline.

1477
02:39:45,902 --> 02:39:50,085
[SPEAKER_06]: Because again, you just don't know what actually will walk through the door when things happen.

1478
02:39:50,645 --> 02:39:59,931
[SPEAKER_06]: So in doing so, we feel like we're setting up the district for success with this size program at this revenue stream.

1479
02:40:00,871 --> 02:40:01,052
[SPEAKER_29]: Great.

1480
02:40:01,072 --> 02:40:04,774
[SPEAKER_29]: Yeah, I just wanted to make sure it was in the balance that you're expecting, which it sounds like it is.

1481
02:40:05,054 --> 02:40:05,754
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, it is.

1482
02:40:06,035 --> 02:40:06,375
[SPEAKER_29]: Good question.

1483
02:40:07,035 --> 02:40:16,846
[SPEAKER_29]: Sort of, I think the kindergarten coordinator, how does that relate to sort of the current staff positions that you have available and understand that we of course have kindergarten in our program?

1484
02:40:17,106 --> 02:40:18,387
[SPEAKER_29]: You created this dedicated role.

1485
02:40:19,328 --> 02:40:20,430
[SPEAKER_29]: Sort of what is the need you're filling?

1486
02:40:20,470 --> 02:40:23,273
[SPEAKER_29]: What are changes that would be implemented by having this role available?

1487
02:40:23,788 --> 02:40:41,680
[SPEAKER_06]: So currently, I think as Annie mentioned earlier in describing the programs as they currently operate, every grade at each of the programs operate in a model similar to what we would recommend that kindergarten does.

1488
02:40:41,740 --> 02:40:45,643
[SPEAKER_06]: So a lead teacher leads the group from one activity to the other.

1489
02:40:46,523 --> 02:40:49,205
[SPEAKER_06]: There's not really choice for that group.

1490
02:40:49,245 --> 02:40:51,567
[SPEAKER_06]: It's like everyone sits down and does this coloring page.

1491
02:40:52,067 --> 02:41:00,456
[SPEAKER_06]: everyone goes down for a snack, everyone in the group goes out to the playground, and that group leader is leading that group around.

1492
02:41:01,037 --> 02:41:11,408
[SPEAKER_06]: So, again, for most of our students, we're recommending that we don't use that model and that grades one through five have more of a choice-based, but kindergarten is different.

1493
02:41:11,908 --> 02:41:13,230
[SPEAKER_06]: Kindergartener enters the year

1494
02:41:14,410 --> 02:41:41,041
[SPEAKER_06]: with a lot, yes, attend preschool programs, but it's their first time in, it's not an accident that kindergarten starts at five years old because it's the first time that a child is able to kind of go from this three to one, four to one ratio, five to one ratio that's in a preschool classroom to you're sitting with 20 peers in a classroom led by one teacher and sitting down at a meeting and kind of waiting your turn

1495
02:41:42,081 --> 02:41:47,926
[SPEAKER_06]: and navigating the social, emotional challenges that are developmentally appropriate for that group.

1496
02:41:48,467 --> 02:41:57,955
[SPEAKER_06]: And so our kindergarten specialist position is currently happening at each of the programs because every grade is led by a group leader.

1497
02:41:58,515 --> 02:42:07,944
[SPEAKER_06]: The difference between what our kindergarten specialist position is and what is currently happening is that this person would be specifically hired for that kindergarten role,

1498
02:42:08,564 --> 02:42:14,709
[SPEAKER_06]: would have the time built in to plan for the kindergarten program each day.

1499
02:42:15,630 --> 02:42:30,663
[SPEAKER_06]: And it's different from the other kindergarten specialists because you're not in a particular domain and trying to meet the wide range of needs for every child to have a STEM experience, for instance, at after school.

1500
02:42:30,703 --> 02:42:33,065
[SPEAKER_06]: But instead, you're thinking of all the different ways that

1501
02:42:33,985 --> 02:42:38,648
[SPEAKER_06]: A child, a five-year-old child, needs to have their needs met in the program.

1502
02:42:38,949 --> 02:42:52,517
[SPEAKER_06]: And that might also mean that you need to play some sort of, it's not a management role, but you need to be able to facilitate a group of, a team of teachers in that space, if you have a very large group, to have station play happening.

1503
02:42:52,923 --> 02:42:59,384
[SPEAKER_06]: to have, if there's four children who are sharing a toy, be there to navigate the social challenges.

1504
02:42:59,404 --> 02:43:01,785
[SPEAKER_06]: Like, how do I share these supplies?

1505
02:43:02,305 --> 02:43:21,568
[SPEAKER_06]: So that job description for that kindergarten specialist is heavy on kind of understanding what the needs are for a kindergarten teacher, and also being able to kind of bring together resources, communicate effectively with colleagues, so that the classroom operates in a way that's best for kindergartners.

1506
02:43:22,475 --> 02:43:23,916
[SPEAKER_29]: Yes, that sounds amazing.

1507
02:43:24,617 --> 02:43:48,076
[SPEAKER_29]: One of the other things that I noticed, I know it's just a possible proposed schedule from the report, but one of the things that I noticed is that you had for the first, second, and third, fifth graders, you had the homework walk first for the first and second, and then the gym game block after, and then you flipped it for the third through fifth graders.

1508
02:43:48,696 --> 02:43:53,483
[SPEAKER_29]: I know it's, of course, not a final schedule by any means, but what were sort of the reasons that brought you to that decision?

1509
02:43:56,362 --> 02:44:05,944
[SPEAKER_25]: So, currently, what is happening, homework is optional and students actually have to say, like parents have to sign a form to say that they're opting their child out of the homework experience.

1510
02:44:05,964 --> 02:44:12,506
[SPEAKER_25]: So, already, homework is not an experience that every family is participating in in the after school experience.

1511
02:44:12,906 --> 02:44:20,948
[SPEAKER_25]: We imagine that that would likely continue on, especially with what we've learned within Medford, the first and second grade homework experience is also quite light.

1512
02:44:21,748 --> 02:44:22,028
[SPEAKER_25]: And so,

1513
02:44:22,508 --> 02:44:34,587
[SPEAKER_25]: knowing that some families will continue to prioritize time in with peers, time with play over homework, and that there are some families that also want that homework to get done, so that way it's not a thing that they have to do at home.

1514
02:44:34,627 --> 02:44:37,732
[SPEAKER_25]: So we want to be able to continue to offer those options.

1515
02:44:38,733 --> 02:44:45,739
[SPEAKER_25]: What we found that specifically, and we know this from our experience, is that older children tend to leave program earlier.

1516
02:44:45,759 --> 02:44:54,226
[SPEAKER_25]: And knowing that you don't want to have a multi-age programming or a large volume of multi-age programming in the gym specifically.

1517
02:44:54,586 --> 02:44:56,688
[SPEAKER_25]: So a lot of this is built around gym time.

1518
02:44:57,148 --> 02:45:04,695
[SPEAKER_25]: So the idea is that we wanted to give opportunity for the oldest children to get a gym activity when the largest volume of them are there.

1519
02:45:05,555 --> 02:45:11,879
[SPEAKER_25]: And then knowing that a lot of them were probably going to be signing themselves out, walking home, and probably then doing homework at home.

1520
02:45:12,099 --> 02:45:19,724
[SPEAKER_25]: The kids that are staying, those third through fifth graders who are staying longer, them having a structured homework time for those kids that stay until six o'clock.

1521
02:45:19,744 --> 02:45:23,987
[SPEAKER_25]: So really kind of understanding the development of what a kid through third and fifth grade would need.

1522
02:45:24,507 --> 02:45:34,255
[SPEAKER_25]: But knowing that also is that, OK, knowing that the third through fifth graders are having the gym time earlier, the first and second graders aren't going to have it until later.

1523
02:45:34,696 --> 02:45:44,924
[SPEAKER_25]: So that same idea of almost a flip-flop where first and second graders can opt in to do their homework earlier, get it done probably 15 minutes, and then the rest of their day is their kind of choices of activities.

1524
02:45:45,345 --> 02:45:49,548
[SPEAKER_25]: So really trying to maximize spaces and also understanding the developmental flow of the day.

1525
02:45:50,209 --> 02:45:50,469
[SPEAKER_29]: Great.

1526
02:45:50,549 --> 02:45:51,309
[SPEAKER_29]: I mean, wonderful.

1527
02:45:52,297 --> 02:45:52,697
[SPEAKER_29]: Absolutely.

1528
02:45:52,797 --> 02:45:54,538
[SPEAKER_29]: I know that you probably have some more questions.

1529
02:45:54,678 --> 02:45:58,621
[SPEAKER_29]: I just wanted to say that I did go to the Brooks program for a few years.

1530
02:45:58,881 --> 02:46:06,525
[SPEAKER_29]: Obviously it was before COVID, but I think one of the most valuable experiences of that was the cross grade stuff.

1531
02:46:07,365 --> 02:46:14,409
[SPEAKER_29]: And so I'm really happy to see that being a priority going into this year as well, the tuition because it's always been.

1532
02:46:16,670 --> 02:46:19,752
[SPEAKER_29]: difficult to get a spot and that was always a concern.

1533
02:46:20,073 --> 02:46:23,034
[SPEAKER_25]: Well we're really excited for the intermixing of grades as well.

1534
02:46:23,094 --> 02:46:27,757
[SPEAKER_25]: We think that there's going to be a lot of students that are going to take a lot from being able to be mentors.

1535
02:46:27,817 --> 02:46:32,200
[SPEAKER_25]: So knowing that a fourth grader can take on a mentorship role

1536
02:46:32,560 --> 02:46:48,676
[SPEAKER_25]: for a first grader, and I know that there's going to be some community concerns about that intermixing, but knowing that when it's well staffed and done well, that there's actually a lot of growth that happens there, and that we'll probably also see a lot of our fourth and fifth graders rising to the occasion in this model.

1537
02:46:49,733 --> 02:46:59,185
[SPEAKER_29]: Yes, and I also, you know, you talked about already like when I asked about the schedule stuff that you are still considering some of the conflicts that can arise from mixing grades.

1538
02:46:59,245 --> 02:47:04,611
[SPEAKER_29]: So I feel somewhat, I don't want to speak for other members, but I feel somewhat confident in this proposal.

1539
02:47:04,631 --> 02:47:05,432
[SPEAKER_29]: So thank you so much.

1540
02:47:05,632 --> 02:47:05,933
[SPEAKER_29]: Absolutely.

1541
02:47:10,608 --> 02:47:11,249
[SPEAKER_14]: Dr. Galussi?

1542
02:47:12,129 --> 02:47:14,431
[SPEAKER_14]: I also, too, just want to comment.

1543
02:47:14,531 --> 02:47:26,019
[SPEAKER_14]: I started by thanking the task force members for their dedication and, like, totally highlighted tonight is two members, Ellen Rushman and Ada Gunning, who are still here.

1544
02:47:26,320 --> 02:47:27,640
[SPEAKER_14]: I'm not sure if they want to speak.

1545
02:47:27,661 --> 02:47:28,341
[SPEAKER_14]: Would you like to?

1546
02:47:28,881 --> 02:47:29,122
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes.

1547
02:47:29,342 --> 02:47:34,065
[SPEAKER_14]: So I do want to make sure we leave some time for them to speak and address the committee.

1548
02:47:36,607 --> 02:47:39,069
[SPEAKER_31]: Are there any other burning questions from our student reps?

1549
02:47:46,419 --> 02:47:53,630
[SPEAKER_22]: I wanted to know if the schedule that we have right now is for like a normal day, because that's what makes up most of the days.

1550
02:47:54,311 --> 02:48:00,721
[SPEAKER_22]: Is this like sort of camp or like PD full day schedule going to kind of reflect that same sort of structure or is it going to be?

1551
02:48:01,262 --> 02:48:02,123
[SPEAKER_22]: something a little different?

1552
02:48:02,323 --> 02:48:03,704
[SPEAKER_25]: It would be something a bit different.

1553
02:48:04,044 --> 02:48:11,008
[SPEAKER_25]: We haven't come up with a mock schedule for that, but that would be something, especially as the NPS moves forward on those PDs.

1554
02:48:11,308 --> 02:48:23,496
[SPEAKER_25]: But what we'd be offering, you know, working with the managing director and site directors as those days get rolled out, is to, you know, what are the number of children that are enrolled, and also the demographics.

1555
02:48:23,616 --> 02:48:24,297
[SPEAKER_25]: Are they younger?

1556
02:48:24,377 --> 02:48:25,037
[SPEAKER_25]: Are they older?

1557
02:48:25,397 --> 02:48:29,280
[SPEAKER_25]: And then how do you create an experience that keeps them engaged?

1558
02:48:29,740 --> 02:48:31,461
[SPEAKER_25]: And so I can speak for our programming.

1559
02:48:31,561 --> 02:48:34,522
[SPEAKER_25]: Our camp programming looks very different than our after school programming.

1560
02:48:35,303 --> 02:48:39,584
[SPEAKER_25]: And it's based around, again, how to keep a full day of students engaged.

1561
02:48:40,165 --> 02:48:45,727
[SPEAKER_25]: So there's not a student schedule yet, but I know that we will be happy to help with the managing director on developing those.

1562
02:48:45,747 --> 02:48:50,629
[SPEAKER_29]: I think that's all.

1563
02:48:50,669 --> 02:48:51,990
[SPEAKER_29]: Do you have anything for me?

1564
02:49:06,009 --> 02:49:06,510
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you all.

1565
02:49:07,531 --> 02:49:08,552
[SPEAKER_31]: I do have one question.

1566
02:49:08,572 --> 02:49:11,134
[SPEAKER_31]: I think it's finally my turn.

1567
02:49:12,936 --> 02:49:24,427
[SPEAKER_31]: I was curious, based on what I am seeing in terms of the recommended capacity, it looks to me like we would anticipate being able to clear two or three wait lists in their entirety.

1568
02:49:24,467 --> 02:49:25,148
[SPEAKER_31]: Is that correct?

1569
02:49:26,428 --> 02:49:28,192
[SPEAKER_06]: That's correct, yes, it would only be the Brooks.

1570
02:49:29,315 --> 02:49:32,843
[SPEAKER_31]: And how many people are we anticipating will remain on the wait list at the Brooks?

1571
02:49:34,344 --> 02:49:40,046
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't know the entire, I mean, I'm guessing it could be as high as 100 students still on the wait list.

1572
02:49:40,406 --> 02:49:40,606
[SPEAKER_31]: Okay.

1573
02:49:40,786 --> 02:49:41,047
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

1574
02:49:41,087 --> 02:49:41,747
[SPEAKER_31]: I appreciate that.

1575
02:49:41,787 --> 02:49:42,147
[SPEAKER_31]: Absolutely.

1576
02:49:42,807 --> 02:49:46,028
[SPEAKER_31]: But, like, thank you for all of your work.

1577
02:49:47,569 --> 02:49:56,112
[SPEAKER_31]: I know we spoke very early in this process, and since then I've been, like, kind of dying to, like, get to a task force meeting and not been able to do it, and I'm just so delighted that you're here.

1578
02:49:56,472 --> 02:50:20,429
[SPEAKER_31]: and I hope we never have to talk about this again, which is why we have talked about it for two and a half hours tonight, but seriously, this is such a big deal for Medford, and it's one that has been a full team effort, and I really, really appreciate you hanging in with us, because I know it was kind of a slow start, and that you are here to help us through these next phases.

1579
02:50:21,630 --> 02:50:24,152
[SPEAKER_31]: Just the collaboration has been really, really wonderful,

1580
02:50:24,672 --> 02:50:27,318
[SPEAKER_31]: and I've only heard fabulous things about your team, so thank you.

1581
02:50:27,338 --> 02:50:32,230
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't know if our task force members would like to say something.

1582
02:50:36,633 --> 02:50:45,919
[SPEAKER_35]: I'm on the task force and I just wanted to thank you all and think basic for all the amazing advances in the after school program.

1583
02:50:46,600 --> 02:50:51,503
[SPEAKER_35]: As you are aware Medford has an after school emergency and has for many years.

1584
02:50:51,724 --> 02:50:55,446
[SPEAKER_35]: It's something that when you move to Medford and you're a parent you hear about right away.

1585
02:50:55,566 --> 02:50:56,787
[SPEAKER_35]: Parents are freaking out.

1586
02:50:57,228 --> 02:50:58,909
[SPEAKER_35]: They're passing stories down the grapevine.

1587
02:50:59,433 --> 02:51:06,496
[SPEAKER_35]: Parents are making plans to go to private school, to Catholic school, all these other schools that are more accommodating of the before and after school needs.

1588
02:51:07,096 --> 02:51:09,156
[SPEAKER_35]: It's something that was on my radar for years.

1589
02:51:10,777 --> 02:51:14,158
[SPEAKER_35]: Prior to the task force being formalized, we did a research project.

1590
02:51:14,178 --> 02:51:24,402
[SPEAKER_35]: Remember, parks was a big part of that, and we compared Medford to neighboring towns, and we were comparatively doing much more poorly than neighboring towns in terms of serving our need.

1591
02:51:25,622 --> 02:51:41,967
[SPEAKER_35]: So, I think anything other than a really bold, ambitious proposal would be incredibly disappointing to parents in Medford, which is why I'm really glad that we're moving forward with this proposal, even though it may cause some nerves on the committee.

1592
02:51:42,167 --> 02:51:46,508
[SPEAKER_35]: I think it's correct to be bold in this moment.

1593
02:51:47,028 --> 02:51:55,419
[SPEAKER_35]: And I want to specifically call out the leadership of Dr. Galussi, because I think before you stepped in, this was really just not going to happen.

1594
02:51:55,439 --> 02:52:03,650
[SPEAKER_35]: I think you've really made this moment, and many of us have stepped in and really pushed this forward, but it would not exist if you weren't here.

1595
02:52:03,770 --> 02:52:04,712
[SPEAKER_35]: So thank you very much.

1596
02:52:06,847 --> 02:52:08,368
[SPEAKER_33]: Just jumping in, my name is Ellen Rushman.

1597
02:52:08,408 --> 02:52:11,530
[SPEAKER_33]: I'm also a parent on the task force.

1598
02:52:11,610 --> 02:52:16,733
[SPEAKER_33]: I have a first grader and a kindergartner in a couple years at the Roberts.

1599
02:52:17,994 --> 02:52:22,897
[SPEAKER_33]: And just to echo Otto's points that this need has been a big deal.

1600
02:52:22,917 --> 02:52:25,259
[SPEAKER_33]: I heard about this right when I moved to Medford.

1601
02:52:25,299 --> 02:52:26,639
[SPEAKER_33]: It was a big stressor for me.

1602
02:52:27,160 --> 02:52:32,263
[SPEAKER_33]: My kid does have an after school spot at a private program, but I'm racing to Medford every day.

1603
02:52:32,723 --> 02:52:33,883
[SPEAKER_33]: to get there by 5 p.m.

1604
02:52:35,084 --> 02:52:40,765
[SPEAKER_33]: So I wanted to really highlight, I mean, we've all talked about the collaboration and how we've worked on this together.

1605
02:52:40,785 --> 02:52:47,167
[SPEAKER_33]: We wouldn't have gotten here without Dr. Galussi, but we wouldn't have gotten here without Dr. Galussi working with the BASIC team.

1606
02:52:48,227 --> 02:52:51,988
[SPEAKER_33]: Andrew, Michael, Annie, and Viviana have been amazing.

1607
02:52:52,472 --> 02:53:02,120
[SPEAKER_33]: We got to visit, I think, the Burbank Elementary School in Belmont early on in this, and it was really exciting to see so many kids running around.

1608
02:53:03,160 --> 02:53:16,331
[SPEAKER_33]: Another thing that we haven't talked about tonight that will be amazing to have more kids at their elementary school is that they will not be riding the bus for 45 minutes to an hour to get wherever they're going after school, which is a huge, huge, huge big deal.

1609
02:53:16,691 --> 02:53:21,535
[SPEAKER_33]: So anyways, thank you all for all of your questions, and I hope that you can be supportive of this.

1610
02:53:21,995 --> 02:53:23,716
[SPEAKER_33]: increase next year and moving forward.

1611
02:53:23,736 --> 02:53:24,417
[SPEAKER_33]: Thanks.

1612
02:53:25,798 --> 02:53:27,178
[SPEAKER_14]: And I just want to quickly comment.

1613
02:53:27,259 --> 02:53:32,402
[SPEAKER_14]: I mean, Ada and Ellen said it as well, even in their comments.

1614
02:53:33,262 --> 02:53:38,266
[SPEAKER_14]: It truly took a village and it all started with their grassroots effort and work.

1615
02:53:39,106 --> 02:53:42,688
[SPEAKER_14]: And we really have worked really nicely and collaboratively as a task force.

1616
02:53:42,788 --> 02:53:45,470
[SPEAKER_14]: So, I thank the task force and BASIC.

1617
02:53:46,011 --> 02:53:49,533
[SPEAKER_14]: It's been truly the emphasis of teamwork.

1618
02:53:52,489 --> 02:53:53,850
[SPEAKER_31]: Is there a motion to approve?

1619
02:53:56,611 --> 02:54:00,593
[SPEAKER_31]: By member Lapate, is there a second by member Parks?

1620
02:54:01,253 --> 02:54:02,114
[SPEAKER_31]: All those in favor.

1621
02:54:02,134 --> 02:54:05,415
[SPEAKER_31]: Oh, we have to do a roll call roll call, please.

1622
02:54:05,435 --> 02:54:11,518
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm Graham.

1623
02:54:12,459 --> 02:54:13,519
[SPEAKER_21]: Yes, I remember Master Boney.

1624
02:54:13,539 --> 02:54:14,860
[SPEAKER_21]: Yes, remember all the party.

1625
02:54:15,080 --> 02:54:17,181
[SPEAKER_21]: Yes, never park parks.

1626
02:54:18,381 --> 02:54:20,362
[SPEAKER_21]: Member Reinfeldt never.

1627
02:54:20,382 --> 02:54:21,503
[SPEAKER_21]: So yes, Marilyn O'Karn.

1628
02:54:22,138 --> 02:54:22,438
[SPEAKER_22]: Yes.

1629
02:54:23,599 --> 02:54:25,440
[SPEAKER_31]: Seven in the affirmative, zero in the negative.

1630
02:54:26,861 --> 02:54:28,182
[SPEAKER_31]: The proposal is approved.

1631
02:54:29,883 --> 02:54:30,744
[SPEAKER_31]: Item number three.

1632
02:54:33,245 --> 02:54:40,050
[SPEAKER_31]: In related fashion, the recommendation for the MPS after school rate card, Dr. Glucy and Will Pippicelli.

1633
02:54:43,112 --> 02:54:43,712
[SPEAKER_14]: Yes, thank you.

1634
02:54:44,513 --> 02:54:46,634
[SPEAKER_14]: Continuing the theme of teamwork.

1635
02:54:48,495 --> 02:54:53,636
[SPEAKER_14]: I also couldn't do any of this without Will Pippicelli, the communications director.

1636
02:54:53,716 --> 02:55:01,617
[SPEAKER_14]: He's just always there, so responsive, so dedicated, so I really appreciate his work with everything.

1637
02:55:01,697 --> 02:55:03,698
[SPEAKER_14]: But we're here to talk about the rate card.

1638
02:55:04,458 --> 02:55:16,240
[SPEAKER_14]: So based on everything you heard tonight, basics recommendations, their study, and their recommendations for our programming, we present

1639
02:55:16,757 --> 02:55:24,551
[SPEAKER_14]: Will is going to walk through the rate card, which is pretty much taking into account their recommendations and moving them forward.

1640
02:55:25,172 --> 02:55:27,176
[SPEAKER_14]: But we're happy to answer any questions.

1641
02:55:27,196 --> 02:55:28,659
[SPEAKER_14]: But I'll let Will kind of talk it through.

1642
02:55:30,060 --> 02:55:30,961
[SPEAKER_18]: Thank you, Dr. Galluzzi.

1643
02:55:31,401 --> 02:55:38,447
[SPEAKER_18]: So I think the big thing about this rate card is there's a multi-day flexibility option.

1644
02:55:38,627 --> 02:55:42,170
[SPEAKER_18]: Previously, we only had the five-day a week, two-day a week, three-day a week.

1645
02:55:43,211 --> 02:55:45,052
[SPEAKER_18]: That caused a lot of confusion for families.

1646
02:55:45,112 --> 02:55:49,235
[SPEAKER_18]: It caused a lot of administrative headaches trying to kind of mix and match days of the week.

1647
02:55:49,856 --> 02:55:58,423
[SPEAKER_18]: So we figured that this system would be very open, very easy to manage on the administrative side.

1648
02:56:04,085 --> 02:56:05,206
[SPEAKER_18]: We've been in and out of the Zoom all night.

1649
02:56:06,767 --> 02:56:12,451
[SPEAKER_18]: And also to really try to place an emphasis on that five-day option.

1650
02:56:12,471 --> 02:56:16,514
[SPEAKER_18]: It is cheaper per day than maybe the one day, the two day, the three day, or the four day.

1651
02:56:17,214 --> 02:56:23,118
[SPEAKER_18]: But even in our early results of asking families to re-enroll, over 80% are all five days.

1652
02:56:23,899 --> 02:56:28,442
[SPEAKER_18]: And there's 95% right now for Tuesday and Wednesday.

1653
02:56:28,482 --> 02:56:30,583
[SPEAKER_18]: So the demand for this program is very high.

1654
02:56:31,712 --> 02:56:42,081
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's why we're trying to work so hard to get an investment that's worth it and that we can sustain all of the wonderful things that we just talked about, but also still be an option for families.

1655
02:56:43,242 --> 02:56:47,706
[SPEAKER_18]: And so they can keep their kids with us and we can provide the proper care that we know we can deliver on.

1656
02:57:00,160 --> 02:57:04,844
[SPEAKER_14]: We're not proposing any changes to the before school program.

1657
02:57:04,864 --> 02:57:07,386
[SPEAKER_14]: This whole entire evening has been about after school care.

1658
02:57:07,826 --> 02:57:09,867
[SPEAKER_14]: We also offer before school care.

1659
02:57:10,708 --> 02:57:19,435
[SPEAKER_14]: We're not proposing any changes to that tuition, but as Will highlighted, there were only specific days.

1660
02:57:19,715 --> 02:57:27,381
[SPEAKER_14]: So what you have here is the reflection of what each day would be for tuition.

1661
02:57:30,147 --> 02:57:33,290
[SPEAKER_31]: I don't know if you want to add anything to that.

1662
02:57:33,310 --> 02:57:34,451
[SPEAKER_31]: Are there, member Reinfeld?

1663
02:57:38,816 --> 02:57:41,899
[SPEAKER_26]: So I am wondering.

1664
02:57:43,892 --> 02:57:49,996
[SPEAKER_26]: what kind of analysis we've done of the need in the people who are re-enrolling.

1665
02:57:50,076 --> 02:57:51,557
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm just thinking this is May.

1666
02:57:51,577 --> 02:57:55,699
[SPEAKER_26]: A lot of people have done their budgeting for the year.

1667
02:57:55,979 --> 02:58:07,866
[SPEAKER_26]: Is there any flexibility to get some sort of incremental assistance on this for people who have made their plans based on

1668
02:58:09,287 --> 02:58:11,888
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm just, I'm concerned about biggest jumps.

1669
02:58:11,968 --> 02:58:12,809
[SPEAKER_26]: I see the need.

1670
02:58:12,889 --> 02:58:13,949
[SPEAKER_26]: I know why we need it.

1671
02:58:13,969 --> 02:58:17,490
[SPEAKER_26]: I know why we want to beef up the programming.

1672
02:58:18,131 --> 02:58:22,912
[SPEAKER_26]: But I am a little bit concerned for families in the system who we're, we're stretching.

1673
02:58:22,932 --> 02:58:26,954
[SPEAKER_26]: I know our rates are, we looked at this last time.

1674
02:58:26,974 --> 02:58:29,075
[SPEAKER_26]: They're a little bit cheaper than private program.

1675
02:58:29,175 --> 02:58:30,255
[SPEAKER_26]: A lot cheaper.

1676
02:58:30,415 --> 02:58:30,795
[SPEAKER_26]: They are.

1677
02:58:30,815 --> 02:58:31,115
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay.

1678
02:58:31,135 --> 02:58:31,316
[SPEAKER_26]: They are.

1679
02:58:31,336 --> 02:58:31,636
[SPEAKER_26]: They are.

1680
02:58:31,656 --> 02:58:32,116
[SPEAKER_26]: A lot cheaper.

1681
02:58:32,256 --> 02:58:34,377
[SPEAKER_26]: So I just, I want to make sure that we're not,

1682
02:58:35,397 --> 02:58:44,481
[SPEAKER_26]: creating hardship for people in the program who have done, who have budgeted already for next year, given how late this is?

1683
02:58:46,102 --> 02:58:52,945
[SPEAKER_14]: The only thing I would say to that, and I'm happy to then have Will extend or the basic team.

1684
02:58:54,228 --> 02:58:57,711
[SPEAKER_14]: this whole endeavor was about increasing capacity.

1685
02:58:58,471 --> 02:59:04,456
[SPEAKER_14]: And so, in any situation, I think there's always going to be a give and a take to that.

1686
02:59:04,957 --> 02:59:16,666
[SPEAKER_14]: We've been very transparent this year about the delay in telling families what the costs are going to be, what it's going to look like, because we've been engaged in this work.

1687
02:59:17,507 --> 02:59:20,549
[SPEAKER_14]: So I do anticipate this is the messy year, but

1688
02:59:22,747 --> 02:59:27,571
[SPEAKER_14]: The whole analysis is built on what we've presented tonight.

1689
02:59:28,192 --> 02:59:32,296
[SPEAKER_14]: So I think we have a lot of flexibility in the sliding scale.

1690
02:59:32,916 --> 02:59:42,845
[SPEAKER_14]: And so those individual the individual work and conversations with families to try and meet them where they're at is where we have to go.

1691
02:59:43,326 --> 02:59:44,127
[SPEAKER_14]: If we're going to

1692
02:59:45,339 --> 02:59:52,743
[SPEAKER_14]: talk about reducing any of this, then we're going to have to talk about, you just voted on the recommendations.

1693
02:59:53,143 --> 02:59:56,765
[SPEAKER_14]: So the recommendations are tied to this rate card.

1694
02:59:56,865 --> 03:00:03,308
[SPEAKER_14]: So if we have to change the rate card, then we're going to have to go back and change the recommendations about positions.

1695
03:00:04,248 --> 03:00:04,848
[SPEAKER_14]: and enrichment.

1696
03:00:05,728 --> 03:00:08,029
[SPEAKER_26]: I am not proposing that we change the rate card.

1697
03:00:08,069 --> 03:00:09,509
[SPEAKER_26]: This makes sense for the budget.

1698
03:00:09,629 --> 03:00:14,030
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm wondering what room there might be for conversations around.

1699
03:00:14,050 --> 03:00:16,430
[SPEAKER_14]: Oh, that's the whole point of the sliding scale.

1700
03:00:16,470 --> 03:00:20,591
[SPEAKER_14]: The whole point of the sliding scale are conversations directly with.

1701
03:00:21,151 --> 03:00:25,632
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, I wasn't quite sure whether the sliding scale.

1702
03:00:26,072 --> 03:00:31,133
[SPEAKER_14]: So the sliding scale, just for people to know, and we'll jump in any time.

1703
03:00:33,306 --> 03:00:36,147
[SPEAKER_14]: We use the state's, the city's sliding scale.

1704
03:00:36,388 --> 03:00:36,608
[SPEAKER_14]: Right.

1705
03:00:36,968 --> 03:00:37,208
[SPEAKER_14]: Right?

1706
03:00:37,288 --> 03:00:40,109
[SPEAKER_14]: So it's the self-declaration of reporting.

1707
03:00:41,210 --> 03:00:46,452
[SPEAKER_14]: That form and the conversation, that form is used in the conversations with the families.

1708
03:00:49,033 --> 03:00:50,414
[SPEAKER_26]: Those are all conversations.

1709
03:00:50,534 --> 03:00:52,095
[SPEAKER_26]: They're not a formula.

1710
03:00:52,115 --> 03:00:52,875
[SPEAKER_26]: Correct.

1711
03:00:52,895 --> 03:00:54,876
[SPEAKER_26]: Because I'm thinking what looks like.

1712
03:00:54,896 --> 03:00:55,717
[SPEAKER_26]: There's no formula.

1713
03:00:55,737 --> 03:00:56,257
[SPEAKER_18]: Okay.

1714
03:00:56,277 --> 03:00:56,477
[SPEAKER_18]: All right.

1715
03:00:57,423 --> 03:01:08,609
[SPEAKER_18]: And then I would also just say if you want to, so the rates, we can only really compare the five, the three, and the two as opposed to four and the one because we don't really have that existing price point because we weren't offering that before.

1716
03:01:08,629 --> 03:01:17,473
[SPEAKER_18]: And each of those three options, it's give or take $60 a month, $15 a week, $3 a day.

1717
03:01:18,253 --> 03:01:25,657
[SPEAKER_18]: So when you kind of think about all the investment we're making not only in our staffing but also in the enrichment that we're trying to offer,

1718
03:01:26,625 --> 03:01:29,787
[SPEAKER_18]: $3 a day, we felt was worth it.

1719
03:01:37,673 --> 03:01:39,174
[SPEAKER_31]: Member Reinfeldt, did you have other questions?

1720
03:01:39,935 --> 03:01:41,075
[SPEAKER_26]: No, I'm just processing.

1721
03:01:41,095 --> 03:01:54,365
[SPEAKER_26]: I think it's good in the information session for people to know where this came from, why it came from, and if there is I'm thinking there might be some hardship that is a one-time hardship, not a

1722
03:01:56,808 --> 03:01:58,170
[SPEAKER_26]: sustained hardship.

1723
03:01:59,050 --> 03:02:08,120
[SPEAKER_26]: So just to know that this is why these scales are in place and this is how to have the conversation around it.

1724
